column85: Cont1 Valve Or Device Fail Ind
column168: Description Of Events

DRIVER EXPERIENCED A SMALL RELEASE WHILE LOADING HIS TRAILER. HE JUST FINISHED CHECKING THE TRAILER AND IT HAD 60% LOADED. AS SOON AS HE RETURNED BACK TO THE TRUCK, HE CHECKED THE MIRROR AND SAW  A STREAM OF OIL BETWEEN THE TRUCK AND TRAILER SO HE SHUT THE PUMP DOWN AND CLOSED THE LOAD LINE. AFTER INVESTIGATING, DRIVER FOUND A PIN HOLE IN THE GO-BETWEEN HOSE.(THE HOSE HAD BEEN REPLACED ONLY 2 MONTHS AGO.) PROPER CLEAN UP WAS DONE. A SAMPLE WILL BE ANALYZED AND SOIL DISPOSED OF PROPERLY.

THE SHIPMENT WAS FOUND TO BE GIVING OFF A STRONG PETROLEUM-BASED ODOR.  THE FREIGHT WAS REMOVED FROM THE SORT FOR A DETERMINATION OF THE CONTENTS AND A REQUEST FOR THE MSDS.  I NOTIFIED THE FAA IN CHICAGO AND SPOKE TO THE DUTY OFFICER.  THE FREIGHT IS BEING HELD PENDING AN FAA INSPECTION.  THERE WERE NO MARKINGS, LABELING, SHIPPING PAPERS NOR OTHER INDICATORS TO LEAD US TO BELIEVE THE CONTENTS WERE REGULATED.

DURING THE SORT THE BOX WAS FOUND TO BE EMITTING A STRONG ODOR.  A SMALL LEAK FROM AROUND THE CLOSURE WAS DETERMINED TO BE THE CAUSE. THE SHIPMENT WAS PLACED IN A SALVAGE DRUM AND RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER.

column42: BATTERIES, WET, FILLED WITH ACID, ELECTRIC STORAGE
column168: TWO BATTERIES THAT ARE NORMALLY CONSIDERED TO BE UNREGULATED BASED ON THEIR DESIGN (NICAD), SOMEHOW ARC'D AND SHORTCIRCUITED.  THIS MALFUNCTION STARTED A FIRE INSIDE THE BOX.  THE FIRE WAS SELF EXTINGUISHED.  THE FAA HAS BEEN NOTIFIED AS HAS THE SHIPPER.  SINCE THE CONTENTS WERE RESPONSIBLE FOR STARTING A FIRE AND THERE WERE NO MARKINGS, LABELING, OR SHIPPING PAPERS WE ARE TREATING THIS AS AN UNDECLARED DANGEROUS GOODS.
THE PRODUCT WAS PLACED ON A SHRINK WRAPPED PALLET DOUBLE STACKED ON TOP OF ANOTHER PALLET.  UPON TRANSIT THE EFFECTED BOX HAD FALLEN AND SOME OF THE PRODUCT HAD SEEPED OUT ONTO THE OUTER CARTON.
OUR DRIVER WAS OFF LOADING AT THE CUSTOMER AND ALL OF A SUDDEN THE HOLDING TANK OVERFLOWED.  CUSTOMER ERROR AND CUSTOMER CLEAN UP.
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column42: PAINT INCLUDING PAINT, LACQUER, ENAMEL, STAIN, SHELLAC SOLUTIONS, VARNISH, POLISH, LIQUID FILLER AND LIQUID LACQUER BASE
column168: THERE WAS NO SPILL AT DECATUR, AL BUT COULD TELL FROM RECENTLY DRIED AND STILL MOIST RESIDUE ON THE DRUM; ONE BESIDE IT.  SENT EARS TO SCM AT FAC & ACSMAT FAC.  NOTIFIED LYNN NEWSOME SAFETY SUPERVISOR.

DOCK EMPLOYEE ATTEMPTED TO UNLOAD 55 GAL DRUM AND DRUM SLIPPED OUT FROM DOLLY AND FELL OVER ON DRUM DOLLY.  BOTTOM FORK OF DRUM DOLLY PUNCTURED BOTTOM EDGE OF PLASTIC DRUM INSIDE TRAILER.  DRUM WAS REMOVED FROM TRAILER AND TURNED UPSIDE DOWN.  SPILLED LIQUID CONTAINER AND CLEANED UP WITH SAND.
AT THE TIME DRIVER WAS FILLING TANK.  DRIVER SET METER CONTROL TO SHUT OFF.  CONTROL FAILED TO CUT OFF.  TRUCK WILL BE REPAIRED AT SHOP.
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column168: THE BOX INVOLVED IN THIS INCIDENT WAS PART OF A SHIPMENT OF 4 BOXES. ONE BOX WAS FOUND TO BE CRUSHED AND SOILED; UPON UNLOADING AT OUR TERMINAL.  THE UNLOADER PUT THE CRUSHED BOX INSIDE ANOTHER BOX AND WRAPPED WITH SHRINK WRAP.  THE SHIPMENT DELIVERED TO THE CONSIGNEE IN PAMPA, TX WITHOUT NOTATION.  UPON OPENING DAMAGED BOX, A WORKER AT CUSTOMER'S RECEIVING AREA SMELLED THE CONTENTS OF THE BOX.  AS A PRECAUTION HE WAS SENT TO MEDICAL CLINIC.  HE WAS LATER RELEASED AND WAS OKAY.  THE CUSTOMER INFORMED ME THAT THEY WOULD DISPOSE OF THE DAMAGED PRODUCT AS THEY HAVE THEIR OWN RESPONSE PEOPLE AND FACILITIES TO TAKE CARE OF THIS INCIDENT.  COY DOCK PEOPLE HAVE BEEN INSTRUCTED NO TO ASSUME THAT JUST BECAUSE BOXES ARE SOILED AND CRUSHED THEY SHOULD RECOUP AND DELIVER. HAZARDOUS MATERIALS THAT SHOW TO BE DAMAGED ARE TO BE EXAMINED AND STOPPED FROM FURTHER TRANSPORTATION AND PROPERLY DISPOSED OF.  WHEN THERE IS THE SLIGHTEST DOUBT, THEY ARE TO CONSULT WITH THEIR SUPERVISOR.  THIS WAS AND OVERSIGHT OF COY DOCK PERSONNEL AS THE HAVE BEEN TRAINED TO HANDLED PROPERLY AND INCIDENTS OF THIS NATURE WILL NOT REOCCUR.
SAMPLE VALVE LEAKING AT DELIVERY POINT.  DROPS WERE CAUGHT IN BUCKET.  APPROXIMATELY 4 OZ.  CHECK SAMPLE VALVE BEFORE LOADING.

WHILE UNLOADING TRAILER, DOCK MAN NOTICED A DRUM OF COPPER LEAKING THAT HAD BEEN CRUSHED BY OTHER FREIGHT THAT HAD SHIFTED.  THE DRUM WAS RECOUPED AND OVERPACKED INTO A DOT APPROVED SALVAGE DRUM AND THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED.  SPILLAGE WAS RECOVERED.
A PAIL WAS FOUND PUNCTURED AFTER LOADED.  THE PAIL WAS RECOUPED AND OVERPACKED INTO A DOT APPROVED SALVAGE PAIL AND THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED.

WHILE UNLOADING TRAILER, A CYLINDER WAS HEARD VENTING. THE VALVES WERE TIGHTENED AND CYLINDER WAS FORWARDED TO DESTINATION.

column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: OUR UNIT WAS ON KY 57 AND APPROXIMATELY 300 FT FROM KY 627 WHEN A CAR APPROACHED OUR UNIT WITH THE BRIGHT LIGHTS ON. OUR DRIVER GOT OVER AS FAR AS HE COULD TO THE RIGHT SIDE OF THE ROADWAY. HIS RIGHT WHEELS DROPPED OFF THE ROAD, AND THE UNIT UPSET ON ITS RIGHT SIDE IN THE DITCH ALONG SIDE THE ROAD. APPROXIMATELY 15 GAL WAS LOST IN THE PROCESS OF TRANSFERRING THE LOAD AND UPRIGHTING THE UNIT.

THE SAFETY-KLEEN DRIVER INSPECTED A LOAD THAT HAD SET OVERNIGHT AND NOTICED THAT THE DRUM HAD LEAKED APPROXIMATELY ONE GALLON OF MATERIAL INTO THE SECONDARY CONTAINMENT OF THE TRUCK.  THE DRIVER ABSORBED THE MATERIAL WITH VERMICULITE.  THE DRUM AND THE ABSORBED MATERIAL WAS OVERPACKED.  THE SPILL GENERATED APPROXIMATELY 15 POUNDS OF WASTE THAT, ALONG WITH THE ORIGINAL MATERIAL, WILL BE SHIPPED TO THE SAFETY-KLEEN TSDF AT 6125 N. PECATONICA RD., PECATONICA, IL 61063 FOR RECYCLING.  THE DRIVER WAS BRIEFED TO CHECK DRUMS FOR LEAKS PRIOR TO LOADING THEM ON HIS VEHICLE.

DRIVER WAS EN ROUTE TO DELIVER THE HAZARDOUS SHIPMENT.  THE FREIGHT WAS SAID TO BE INTACT AT THE PREVIOUS STOP.  AT THE PREVIOUS STOP. WHEN HE OPENED THE DOOR AT THE CUSTOMERS DOCK, HE NOTICED THE CONTENTS OF ONE PAIL SPILLED ON THE TRAILER FLOOR.  THE SHIPPER AND CHEMTREC WERE CALLED FOR HANDLING INSTRUCTIONS.  ABSORBENT MATERIAL WAS USED TO CLEAN TO SPILL.  THE PACKAGES WERE NOT PROPERLY SECURED BY THE DRIVER AND PACKAGING DOES NOT APPEAR TO BE THE PROBLEM.  THE DRIVER HAD JUST VIEWED THE HAZARDOUS MATERIAL TRAINING FILM A WEEK EARLIER.  HE HAD BEEN ISSUED AN INCIDENT REPORT AND WILL BE RE-TRAINED.

THE DRIVER BROUGHT THE PACKAGE BACK TO THE SHIPPER THE FOLLOWING DAY AND EXPLAINED THAT HE MUST HAVE A CONTRACT WITH UPS IN ORDER TO SHIP HAZARDOUS MATERIALS. A DECISION WAS MADE TO OPEN THE BOX AND THEY DISCOVERED THE PACKAGE THAT HAD BEEN RETURNED THAT MORNING WAS PLACED INSIDE FOR SHIPMENT, EVEN THOUGH IT WAS EXPLAINED THAT HE COULD NOT SHIP THIS MERCHANDISE WITHOUT A CONTRACT AND CORRECT LABELING. column168: CROWN VEHICLE 215222/87 WAS TRAVELING EAST BOUND ON I565, DRIVER HARRY NETTLES.  AT APPROXIMATELY 0145 HOURS, CROWN VEHICLE STROKE AN ABANDONED PICKUP PARKED ON THE RIGHT HAND SHOULDER OF I565 JUST PRIOR TO EXIT 19.  AFTER STRIKING THE PICKUP, CROWN VEHICLE PROCEEDED EAST BOUND ALONG GUARD RAIL, AND BROKE THROUGH GUARD RAIL. CROWN VEHICLE TRAVELED DOWN A STEEP EMBANKMENT.  UPON STRIKING BOTTOM OF EMBANKMENT, VEHICLE CRASHED AND CRASHED AND CAUGHT FIRE. VEHICLE WAS LOADED WITH 8900 GALLONS OF GASOLINE.  ALL GALLONS OF GASOLINE WERE BURNT UP IN THE ACCIDENT/FIRE.  GASOLINE/ FIRE ENTERED STORM SEWER AND PROCEEDED FOR APPROXIMATELY 1/4 MILE FROM THE ACCIDENT SIGHT.  THE CROWN VEHICLES WERE DESTROYED IN THE ACCIDENT/FIRE.  VEHICLE/PRODUCT FIRE CAUGHT FIRE IN THE IMMEDIATE. TWO PARKED CARS PARKED AT 3015 2ND AVENUE RECEIVED SLIGHT FIRE DAMAGE.

Delta employee was loading sulfuric acid into a common carrier. The carrier had been loaded and the delta employee was going to clear the loading hose with air pressure. When the air pressure was applied to the loading hose it jumped out of the tanker manhole and sprayed approximately 3-4 gallons of sulfuric acid into the air. The loading hose was secured to the manhole cover by a rubber strap. The strap was still in place when the loading hose came out of the tanker. The spray was picked up by a strong wind and was blown onto the delta employees vehicle. The vehicle was neutralized with water. The spray was the only result of the incident. Nothing else was affected except for the vehicle.

column168: AT 1750 HRS, ON 10-09-98, A SWITCH CREW WAS PULLING AN ADJACENT TRACK WHEN THEY NOTICED GATX 22611, A TANK CAR CONTAINING ISOPROPENYLBENZENE, A FLAMMABLE LIQUID, LEAKING FROM THE TOP OF THE CAR. BOTH CREW MEMBERS COMPLAINED OF EYE IRRITATION AND WERE TAKEN TO A NEAR BY HOSPITAL, BOTH WERE TREATED AND RELEASED. THE CAR WAS ISOLATED AND AN ENVIRONMENTAL RESPONSE CONTRACTOR WAS CALLED TO MAKE REPAIRS. BEFORE MAKING THE REPAIRS THEY FOUND THE MANWAY COVER GASKET DEFECTIVE.: TWO MANWAY BOLTS HANGING LOOSE: AND THE REST OF THE BOLTS WERE ONLY FINGER TIGHT. TO CORRECT THE LEAKING CONDITIONS A NEW GASKET WAS APPLIED AND ALL MANWAY BOLTS WERE REPOSITIONED AND TIGHTENED. NO PRODUCT SPILLED TO THE GROUND SO NO ADDITIONAL CLEANUP WILL BE NECESSARY I CONNECTION TO THIS INCIDENT.

ON 10-07-98, AT 0825HRS, A RAILROAD TANK CAR, UTLX 99058, LOADED WITH AMMONIA, ANHYDROUS, LIQUIFIED, WAS OBSERVED LEAKING FROM THE TOP OF THE CAR WHILE BEING SWITCHED AT BEAUMONT, TX RAIL YARD. THE SHIPPER WAS IMMEDIATELY NOTIFIED AND DISPATCHED THEIR EMERGENCY RESPONSE CREW TO THE SCENE. THE SHIPPER TIGHTENED THE PACKING GLAND ON THE LIQUID VALVE STEM STOPPING THE LEAK AT 10:00AM ON THE SAME DAY. THE TANK CAR WAS THEN SWITCHED BACK INTO SHIPPPER'S PLANT FOR VALVE REPLACEMENT.

ON 10-10-98, AT APPROX. 1946 HRS., A RAILROAD TANK CAR, REPORTING # TCDX 13068, LOADED SULFURIC ACID, WHILE BEING SWITCHED AT KCS ARTESIA, MS., RAIL YARD RELEASED SULPHURIC ACID THRU A DEFECTIVE RUPTURED DISK. THE RELEASE OCCURRED A COUPLING OPERATION, WHEN THE TANK CAR WAS COUPLED TO ANOTHER CAR, WERE THE LADING SLOSHED IN THE TANK CAR AND RELEASED THRU THE DEFECTIVE RUPTURED DISK, HITTING A KCS CONDUCTOR WORKING ON THE GROUND. THE CONDUCTOR RECEIVED MINOR SPLATTER TO HIS LEFT HAND, ARM, LEFT SIDE OF HIS NOSE AND BEHIND HIS EAR. THE EMPLOYEE IMMEDIATELY RINSED THE AFFECTED AREAS WITH COPIOUS AMOUNTS OF WATER AND THEN PROCEEDED TO THE STARKVILLE, MS. HOSPITAL FOR MEDICAL EVALUATION. WHILE AT THE HOSPITAL THE EMPLOYEE WAS RINSED OFF AGAIN AND WAS PRESCRIBED A BURN CREAM. THE EMPLOYEE WAS RELEASED FROM THE HOSPITAL WITH MINOR BURNS SPOTS TO HIS ARM , EAR AND NOSE. THE TANK CAR WAS IMMEDIATELY ISOLATED TO PREVENT FURTHER MOVEMENT AND POSSIBLE SPILLAGE. THE SHIPPER WAS IMMEDIATELY NOTIFIED AND DISPATCHED A REPAIR CREW TO THE SCENE, REPAIRING THE DEFECTIVE RUPTURED DISK.

column168: Air products trailer 51-7216 had been parked at 7a.m., 10/11/98, at a staging area in Exton, PA in preparation for a purging operation of a 30 mile section of a petroleum pipeline which runs through Exton, PA. The trailer had been parked securely for 19 hours as three other trailers were brought to the purge site for the purge job at 2a.m. on 10/12/98. The local police notified the air products emergency operator in Allentown, Pa, that they noticed vapors coming from trailer 51-7216. A fifth trailer was being dispatched from our terminal in Lancaster, Pa. and our driver was advised that 51-7216 was releasing vapors from it's rear cabinet. At this time the driver leaving Lancaster was the closest response person to the scene. When the driver arrived in Exton at 4 a.m. he inspected the trailer emitting the vapors and then he tightly closed the fill/ withdrawal valve, stopping the leak which had developed due to the warming of the valve and a slight inner vessel pressure rise due to the extended parking time. The trailer was secured without further incident. There was no damage to equipment on the surrounding area.

column168: ILLINOIS CENTRAL RAILROAD CARMAN NOTICED CAR UTLX 641758 LEAKING PRODUCT AND VAPOR FROM AROUND THE MANWAY DURING HIS INSPECTION. FIRE DEPARTMENT, STATE POLICE, CHEMTREC, AND THE SHIPPER CALLED. SHIPPER RESPONSE TEAM WOULD BE OUT HOUSTON, TX AND WOULD TAKE SOME TIME TO GET TO THE SCENE.  SHIPPER OKAYED ILLINOIS CENTRAL TO ATTEMPT TO STOP THE LEAK AND REPAIR IF POSSIBLE.  MR. HERMAN NEWELL OF THE ILLINOIS CENTRAL RAILROAD INSPECTED THE MANWAY AREA AND FOUND THAT MOST OF THE MANWAY GASKET WAS MISSING AND ONE I BOLT WAS STRIPPED.  MR NEWELL REPLACE THE MANWAY GASKET WITH A NEW ONE WHICH STOPPED THE LEAK BUT WOULD NOT RELEASE THE CAR BACK TO TRANSPORTATION WITH THE STRIPPED I  BOLT.  TANK CAR WAS PUT ON THE RIP TRACK AND SHIPPER WAS CALLED.  SHIPPER SENT UTLX MOBILE REPAIR TEAM TO REPLACE THE BOLT 10/20/98 AND CAR WAS THEN RELEASED BACK TO TRANSPORTATION.

DURING THE PM LOADING OPERATION, THIS SHIPMENT WAS DISCOVERED CRUSHED AND LEAKING APPROX. ONE LITER OF CONTENTS. FURTHER INVESTIGATION REVEALED  THE PACKAGE TO CONTAIN A METAL CAN WITH MARKINGS AND LABELLINGS NOTED TO CONTAIN FLAMMABLE ADHESIVES. THE OUTER PACKAGE WAS NOT MARKED, LABELLED OR DOCUMENTED TO CONTAIN DANGEROUS GOODS. THE LAX FAA OFFICE WAS NOTIFIED OF THE SHIPMENT FOR THE SHIPMENT FOR INVESTIGATION. SHIPMENTS ARE BEING HELD FOR FAA REVIEW.

THIS PACKAGE BEGAN LEAKING DURING THE FEDEX COURIER'S DELIVERY CYCLE AND SPILLED ABOUT 1L OF LIQUID ON THE BOX AND FLOORBOARD OF THE DELIVERY VEHICLE. THE SPILL CLEANUP SPECIALIST RESPONDED AND CLEANED UP THE SPILL PER FEDEX GUIDELINES. DURING THE INSPECTION OF THE INNER CONTAINER. IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE CAP/ CLOSURE ON THE INNER CONTAINER WAS LOOSE, CAUSING THE SPILL. THIS IS A HIDDEN DISCREPENCY, SINCE THE INNER PLASTIC CONTAINER HAD OVER 2.5 L AND THERE WAS NO INTERMEDIATE  PACKAGING OF RIGID PLASTIC OR METAL. THE FAA WAS CONTACTED ABOUT THIS DISCREPENCY AND DISPOSITION OF THE PACKAGE IS PENDING.

DURING SORT OPERATIONS IT APPEARS THIS PACKAGE WAS DROPPED / DAMAGED BREAKING A CAP ON THE TOP OF ONE OF THE INNER PLASTIC BOTTLES. THE SHIPMENT WAS PLACED INSIDE  A SALVAGE DRUM AND HELD PENDING DISPOSITION INSTRUCTIONS FROM THE CUSTOMER.

column168: Two of six manway cover securement bolts loose, scmx 2718, October 26, 1998, Pittsburgh Division. At approximately 1015 hours on Monday, October 26, 1998, at Conrail's Conway yard in Conway, PA, a Conrail yard crew noted product on top of tank car scmx 2718, containing petroleum distillates, n.o.s. At approximately 1430 hours, Conrail's hazardous material field service manager arrived at the site and upon further examination, determined that the tank car had two of six manway cover securement bolts loose. Repairs were made by Conrail's hazardous material field service manager who tightened two of six manway cover securement bolts. The tank car was okayed for transportation and sent to destination.

Six of six manway cover securement bolts loose, gatx 97694, October 11, 1998, Philadelphia division. At approximately 1350 hours, Sunday, October 11, 1998, at Conrail's Oak Island yard in Newark, NJ, a Conrail car foreman noted an odor emanating from tank car gatx94694, containing ethyl acrylate, inhibited. At approximately 1540 hours, conrail's terminal general foreman arrived at the site and upon further examination, determined that the tank car had six of six manway cover securement bolts loose. Repairs were made by Conrail's terminal general foreman who tightened six of six manway cover securement bolts. The tank car was okayed for transportation and sent to destination.

Inbound train inspection at Havre revealed trailer leaking and product pooling on the flat car. Trailer isolated and inspection of contents indicated that improper blocking resulted in load shift and a pallet punctured a plastic drum of cleaning product. Olympus contracted to clean the flat car and the trailer. Patrick construction contracted to adjust and re-block trailer load.

During a southbound movement a Buffalo & Pittsburgh Railroad train derailed south of Ridgeway, PA at approximately 1834 hours. Upon investigation, the railroad conductor observed that twelve cars derailed. Five of the derailed cars were carrying sulfuric acid; one of the five leaked. A vapor cloud from the acid moved towards the head end of the train and in the direction of the small rural community of Portland Mills, PA. The train's engineer was exposed to the vapors and was taken to a local hospital for observation. He was released the following day. The Ridgeway Fire and Rescue was called at 1837. Elk County Hazmat team was notified shortly after. The incident commander from Ridgeway Fire and Rescue ordered that approximately 180 residents of the Portland Mills community be evacuated as a precaution. All other application regulatory agencies were advised. The railroad's emergency response contractor was called and arrived at approximately 0240 hours on 10/6/98. Much of the spilled acid was contained by the railroad road bed and kept away from the Clarion River. The contained material and surrounding soil was neutralized with lime and transported to a local certified landfill near Ridgeway. Approximately 1,500 ton of contaminated soil was removed. There are no other environmental concerns anticipated at this time. The PA department of environmental Protection was at the site during the clean up phase. The derailed tank cars were re-railed by Hulcher Services and moved by special FRA exemption to Bradford, PA for transloading into other tank cars and then on to the Buffalo and Pittsburgh's Shop in Butler, PA for evaluation and disposition.

Switch crew reported car leaking. Investigation by BNSF and shipper responders revealed failed safety relief valve (SRV). Responders were able to stop release and car was moved back to the shipper for repair. Shipper will report back to carrier with cause of SRV failure.

Container reporter on its side in lot 1 and leaking. BNSF DPS responder reported one chassis leg had broken off at failed weld, causing the container to tip over, which resulted in one plastic bottle of product to be crushed and contents evaporated.

After switching car, switch crew reported product splashed out of top spring loaded 75 psi srv due to excessive lateral forces that resulted from a switching joint made on a descending grade in Slaton yard. BNSF responder checked car finding that the SRV had re-seated and no further product loss incurred. Environmental contractor neutralized product on equipment, rail and affected roadbed ground area. Car released to destination.

Conductor on inbound train reported a container leaking. Inspection by BNSF responder found drum in front corner leaking, as it was placed atop a lashing ring welded to the side wall which in turn wore a hole in the lower chime. Contractor assisted in transloading the remainder of the drums along with  the subject drum (now placed inside a salvage drum) to another shipping container.

Yard master reported an odor emanating from car after arrival at Whitefish. No product was leaking after visual inspection, Mechanical response team tightened manway bolts and odor was eliminated. The car was released to its destination.

Car arrived in Havre and yard personnel noticed that the product was leaking out top 75 psi srv. Leakage stopped and investigation revealed that the car was overloaded. Spilled product was remediated.

Broken stainless steel tube on the safety relief device, utlx 80020, October 1, 1998, Albany Division. At approximately 1115 hours, Thursday, October 1, 1998, at Conrail's West Springfield Yard in West Springfield, MA, a Conrail car inspector discovered vapors coming from the side of tank car UTLX 80020 containing Argon, refrigerated liquid. At approximately 1340 hours, the consignee, Praxair from Suffield, Connecticut arrived at the site, examined the car and determined that it had a broken stainless steel tube on the safety relief device. Repairs were made by Praxair who replaced the broken tube with a new stainless steel tube. At 1700 hours, the tank car was secured, okayed for transportation and sent to destination.

column168: Freight was received in Harrisburg, Pennsylvania off of trailer werner 98641, on a terminal to terminal bill with the contents leaking from both ends of the container. Container was placed in an overpack and Chemtrec and the shipper were notified and an msds was received. The material on the floor of the trailer was neutralized in accordance with the msds and debris was placed in an overpack container. Material and residue will be disposed of in accordance with all local, state and federal laws, by Environmental Products and Services.

The damaged drum was received at the Lexington terminal from another Overnite terminal, already inside of a metal recovery drum. I (preparer) could not do an inspection of the drum because when I (preparer) removed the recovery lid off of the recovery drum, the fumes were too intense from the leakage to proceed any further. I (preparer) then placed the recovery lid back on the drum. The incident took place at the Overnite Service Center in Mount Pleasant, Pennsylvania. A forklift operator was loading a skid of freight on top of the drums on an outbound trailer. The blades were sticking out of the other side of the skid and one of the blades struck one of the drums in its side, puncturing it. The damaged drum was put into a recovery drum and sent on. The forklift operator was counselled for his negligence.

Freight was received in Harrisburg, Pennsylvania, with the two drums on a skid. During transportation, the slats on the skid were broken and one of the drums fell through the slats and were on the base of the skid. During unloading, the  plastic drum was punctured causing the release of the liquid onto the floor of the trailer. Absorbent was placed on the floor of the trailer and spilled material was absorbed. The drum was placed in an overpack and was returned to the shipper per Marion Cunningham and shipper. Debris will be disposed of in accordance with all local, state and federal laws.

TANK TRUCK VALVE IN AN OPEN POSITION WHEN TRANSLOADING, PROX 64078. OCTOBER 9, 1998, ALBANY DIVISION.  AT APPROXIMATELY 0700 HOURS, FRIDAY, OCTOBER 9, 1998, AT CONRAIL'S WEST ALBANY YARD, ALBANY, NEW YORK, A GAS SUPPLY RESOURCE TERMINAL MANAGER DISCOVERED PRODUCT SPILLING FROM THE REAR VALVE OF KRAMER CHEMICALS TANK TRUCK DURING TRANSLOADING FROM PROX 64078 CONTAINING SODIUM HYDROXIDE.  AT APPROXIMATELY 0705 HOURS, A BULK TRANSLOADING SUPERVISOR ARRIVED AT THE SITE, EXAMINED THE TANK TRUCK AND DETERMINED THAT THE TRUCK VALVE WAS IN AN OPEN POSITION WHEN TRANSLOADING COMMENCED.  UPON NOTIFICATION, A BT&T TRANSFER OPERATOR IMMEDIATELY SHUT OFF PRODUCT TRANSFER.   CLEAN HARBORS, AN ENVIRONMENTAL REMEDIATION CONTRACTOR CLEANED THE SPILLED AREA.  PROX 64078 WAS OKAYED FOR TRANSPORTATION AND SENT TO DESTINATION.

column168: THE AIR PRODUCTS DRIVER WAS BEGINNING TO MAKE A DELIVERY BY PURGING HIS TRANSFER HOSE AND PUMP SYSTEM.  THE DRIVER ERRORED IN HIS DELIVERY PROCEDURE BY ALLOWING THE EXISTING PRODUCT IN THE CUSTOMERS RECEIVING TANK TO BACK FLOW INTO THE DELIVERY TANKER, CAUSING THE TANKER TO BECOME OVER FULL ALLOWING PRODUCT TO VENT FROM THE DELIVERY TANKER.  THIS EVENT CAUSED VAPORING PRODUCT TO SPILL FROM THE  TANKER.  POLICE AND FIRE DEPARTMENT ASSISTANCE WAS CALLED. ONCE THE BACK FLOW WAS STOPPED THE SPILLAGE AND PRODUCT VAPORING STOPPED.  THE DRIVER WAS THEN ABLE TO MAKE THE PRODUCT DELIVERED WITHOUT FURTHER INCIDENT.  WHEN THE VEHICLE RETURNED TO THE AIR PRODUCTS PLANT THE DRIVER WAS COUNSELLED REGARDING HIS ERROR AND THE CARGO TANKER WAS INSPECTED IT WAS FOUND THAT THE TRAILER DISCHARGE VALVE WAS BROKEN WHICH ALLOWED PRODUCT TO BACK FLOW.  A PROPER CHECK VALVE WOULD HAVE CORRECTED THE DRIVER ERROR.  THE CHECK VALVE WAS REPLACED AND THE TRAILER WAS PLACED BACK IN SERVICE.

column168: DRIVER WAS MAKING A DELIVERY OF 6,500 GALLONS OF DENATURE ALCOHOL TO THE CONSIGNEE'S STORAGE TANK WHICH WAS LOCATED UNDERGROUND.  UNAWARE THAT THE STORAGE TANK DID NOT HAVE SUFFICIENT CAPACITY AVAILABLE TO CONTAIN ENTIRE LOAD, OFF LOADING PROCEEDED UNTIL PRODUCT SPEW OUT OF THE VENT LINE.  THERE WAS APPROXIMATELY 20 GALLONS OF MATERIALS SPILLED.  THE CONSIGNEE HAS CLEANED UP BY EXCAVATING THE SOIL AT THE SITE AND THEY ARE HANDLING THE DISPOSAL.  RELEASE WAS SOLELY DUE TO INABILITY OF STORAGE TANK TO HOLD MATERIAL.  THERE WAS NO FAILURE OF EQUIPMENT AND NO ERROR ON THE PART OF THE DRIVER.

column168: ON FRIDAY MORNING,10-09-98 AT 2:45 A.M., I HAD OPENED THE DOOR OF A TRAILER THAT WAS TO OUR DOCK. THIS WAS A STRIPPER FROM CARTERET, N.J., I NOTICED A BOX OF CORROSIVE MATERIAL WAS LEAKING AND BEGINNING TO REACT WITH THE WATER ON THE FLOOR OF THE TRAILER. I CALLED THE FIRE DEPT AND WHEN THEY ARRIVED, THEY CALLED D.E.P., THEN I CALLED OUR CONTRACTOR FOR HAZ MAT CLEANUP (D-TOX). WE WERE EVACUATED FOR ABOUT TWO HOURS WHILE THEY CLEANED UP.

55 GAL. DRUM LOADED ON TRAILER BY FORKLIFT USING DRUM ATTACHMENT DEVICE. FORKLIFT OPERATOR APPARENTLY PUNCTURED AND DAMAGED TO SOME EXTENT THAT CAUSED DRUM TO FAIL DURING TRANSIT. DRIVER DISCOVERED LEAK DURING TRANSIT AND CALLED FOR EMERGENCY RESPONSE PERSONNEL FOR HELP. FORKLIFT OPERATOR TO BE NOTIFIED OF INCIDENT, INSTRUCTIONS IN PROPER USE OF EQUIPMENT, AND CORRECTIVE ACTION TO BE PLACED IN PERSONNEL FILE.

column168: DOCK MAN DISCOVERED THE DAMAGED PAILS AS HE WAS LOADING FREIGHT FROM THE INBOUND TRAILER. THE PREVIOUS LOADING FACILITY HAD PLACED A JACK WEIGHING 2070 LBS. ON TOP OF PALLETS OF BOOKS AND PALLETS OF CLUTCHES. THE JACK WAS NOT BLOCKED IN PROPERLY SO IT TIPPED OVER IN TRANSIT AND CRUSHED TWO PAILS. THE PAILS WERE TRANSFERRED TO OS&D AND PLACED IN A RECOVERY DRUM FOR DISPOSAL BY AN ENVIRONMENTAL CONTRACTOR. COMPANY PROCEDURES MANDATES THAT THE INDIVIDUAL RESPONSIBLE FOR IMPROPERLY LOADING THE JACK RECEIVE CORRECTIVE ACTIONS TO PREVENT FURTHER OCCURRENCES.

DOCK HAND, CRANSTON "DUKE" PHELIA, WAS UNLOADING DRUM WITH A BARREL TRUCK. WHEN HE ROLLED IT OVER THE DOCK PLATE, THE DRUM BOUNCED OFF THE DRUM DOLLY AND FELL TO THE TRAILER FLOOR. THE LID POPPED OFF CAUSING SPILLAGE. THE DRUM WAS UP RIGHTED AND THE LID REPLACED ON IT.

column42: PAINT RELATED MATERIAL INCLUDING PAINT THINNING, DRYING, REMOVING, OR REDUCING COMPOUND
column168: WHILE THE DRIVER WAS UNLOADING THE DRUM, THE BUNG POPPED OUT AND SPILLED TWO GALLONS OF MATERIAL ONTO  THE LOADING DOCK. THE DRIVER USED ABSORBENT PADS TO CLEAN UP THE SPILLED MATERIAL. THE ABSORBENT PADS WERE PLACED INTO A SLUDGE DRUM. THIS SPILL GENERATED 30 POUNDS OF WASTE THAT WILL BE TRANSPORTED, ALONG WITH THE ORIGINAL WASTE, TO THE SAFTEY KLEEN FACILITY AT 1722 COOPER CREED RD, DENTON, TX 76208 FOR RECYCLING. THE DRIVER WAS COUNSELED TO INSPECT FITTINGS FOR PROPER INSTALLATION AND TO USE MORE CARE WHEN UNLOADING DRUMS FOR HIS VEHICLE.

WHILE TRANSFERRING LIQUID WASTE MATERIAL AT THE PROCESSING FACILITY THE DRIVER NEGLECTED TO CHANGE THE VALVE SETTINGS PRIOR TO DISCONNECTING A HOSE AND SPILLED 25 GALLONS OF COMBUSTIBLE LIQUIDS INTO SECONDARY CONTAINMENT . THE DRIVER USED ABSORBENT PADS AND A MOP TO CLEAN UP THE SPILL AND DRUMMED THE WASTE. THIS SPILL GENERATED 300 POUNDS OF WASTE THAT WILL BE, ALONG WITH THE ORIGINAL WASTE, TRANSPORTED TO THE SAFETY-KLEEN FACILITY AT 1000 SOUTH I ST, REEDLEY, C.A. 93654 FOR RECYCLING. THE DRIVER WAS COUNSELED ON FOLLOWING THE PROPER VALVE OPERATION SEQUENCE WHEN PUMPING WASTE FROM HIS TANKER.
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column168: WHILE CHECKING HIS VEHICLE DURING A REFUELING STOP THE DRIVER NOTICED A LIQUID LEAKING FROM THE BACK OF HIS TRUCK ONTO THE ASPHALT PARKING AREA. THE DRIVER PLACED ABSORBENT PADS AND VERMICULITE UNDER THE LEAK AND NOTIFIED HIS DISPATCHER OF THE INCIDENT TO OBTAIN FURTHER DIRECTION. LOCAL AUTHORITIES WERE NOTIFIED AND DECIDED TO EVACUATE TEN PEOPLE FROM A NEARBY TRUCK STOP UNTIL A SPILL TEAM COULD RESPOND AND POSITIVELY IDENTIFY THE LEAKING MATERIAL. A COMMERCIAL EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR AS CONTACTED BY THE VANZANT COUNTY SHERIFF'S DEPT. TO RESPOND AND CLEAN-UP THE SPILL. THE CONTRACTOR DETERMINED THAT THE LEAK WAS CAUSED BY LOOSE LID MISSING A RETAINING BOLT AND THAT THE LEAKING MATERIAL WAS A SOLVENT. THE CONTRACTOR CLEANED UP THE SPILLED MATERIAL AND PLACED IT INTO A 85 GAL OVERPACK. THE CONTRACTOR ALSO PLACED A NEW BOLT IN THE LID OF THE 30 GAL DRUM AND SECURED THE LID. THIS LEAK GENERATED APPROX. 60 POUNDS OF WASTE THAT WAS, ALONG WITH THE ORIGINAL WASTE, SHIPPED TO THE SAFETY-KLEEN FACILITY AT 1722 COOPER CREEK RD, DENTON,TX 76208 WHERE IT WAS RECYCLED. THE DRIVER WAS COUNSELED TO CLOSELY INSPECT THE DRUM SEALING DEVICES UPON LOADING AND PERIODICALLY DURING SHIPMENT TO  AVOID SIMILAR OCCURRENCES.

THE DRIVER INSPECTED HIS TRAILER AND NOTICED A LEAK O THE GROUND UNDER THE TRAILER. THE DRIVER PLACED A CONTAINER UNDER THE LEAK AND REPORTED THE LEAK TO A SUPERVISOR. THE SUPERVISOR DISPATCHED A SPILL TEAM THAT LOCATED THE OVERPACKED THE LEAKING 55 GAL DRUM INTO AN 85 GAL OVER PACK. THE SPILL TEAM ALSO ABSORBED THE MATERIAL THAT HAD LEAKED INTO THE TRAILER AND SHOVELED UP THE GRAVEL AND SOIL AND THE ABSORBED MATERIAL WAS ALL PLACED INTO THE SAME OVER PACK AS THE DRUM. THIS LEAK GENERATED APPROX. 80 POUNDS OF WASTE THAT WILL BE, ALONG WITH THE ORIGINAL WASTE, TRANSPORTED TO THE SAFETY-KLEEN FACILITY AT 3700 LA GRANGE RD., SMITHFIELD,KY 40068 FOR RECYCLING.

column62: Loose Closure, Component, or Device; Dropped
column168: THE DRIVER DROPPED THE 16 GALLON DRUM WHILE UNLOADING IT WHICH CAUSED THE LID TO POP OFF DUE TO THE RETAINING BOLT BEING LOOSE. THIS RESULTED IN A SPILL OF NINE GALLONS OF SOLVENT ONTO A PAVED AREA. THE SPILL WAS ABSORBED BY THE DRIVER WITH PADS. THE ABSORBED MATERIAL WAS PLACED INTO THE 16 GALLON, THE LID WAS REPLACED AND SECURED. THIS SPILL GENERATED 90 POUNDS OF WASTE THAT WAS, ALONG WITH HE ORIGINAL WASTE, TRANSPORTED TO THE SAFETY-KLEEN FACILITY AT 150 PENROD CT, GLEN BURNIE, M.D. 21061 FOR TEMPORARY STORAGE PRIOR TO FINAL SHIPMENT TO ANOTHER SAFETY-KLEEN FACILITY FOR RECYCLING. THE DRIVER WAS COUNSELED TO CLOSELY INSPECT ALL CLOSURES ON DRUMS PRIOR TO LOADING OR UNLOADING THEM FROM HIS VEHICLE.

TANK IS NORMALLY FITTED WITH A PROTECTIVE PLATE UNDER THE DISCHARGE VALVE. THE PROTECTIVE PLATE WAS MISSING FROM THE SUBJECT TANK. THE VALVE HANDLE WAS ORIENTED SUCH THAT WHEN CLOSED, IT EXTENDED BELOW THE BOTTOM OF THE TANK. WHEN THE TANK WAS PLACED ONTO A PALLET, IT RESTED ON THE HANDLE. THE VALVE NIPPLE CRACKED FROM THE FORCE AGAINST IT, RESULTING IN LOSS OF THE PRODUCT. THE CONTAINER WAS SECURED AND RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER.

DRIVER WAS IN PROCESS OF PUMPING OFF LOAD OF FUEL. THE COME LOCK CAP FITTING ON THE OFF SIDE OF THE TRAILER VIBRATED LOOSE AND SPRAYED FUEL. WE KEEP TIE DOWNS ON ALL THE FITTINGS BUT DRIVER FORGOT TO CHECK THE CAP TO MAKE SURE IT WAS TIED DOWN. WE REMOVED COME LOCK CAP FITTING AND PUT A PIPE CAP ON THE OFF SIDE TO PREVENT THE INCIDENT FROM HAPPENING AGAIN. ANTELOPE COAL CLEANED UP SPILL AND DISPOSED OF SOIL.

DRIVER DISCOVERED LEAKING PALLET AT RECEIVER. UPON INSPECTION OF THE PALLET IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT THE SPILL WAS CAUSED BY A DEFECTIVE LID ON THE CONTAINER. NO PRODUCT HAD REACHED THE FLOOR OF THE TRAILER. RECEIVER ACCEPTED THE PALLET AND MANAGED THE CLEAN UP PROCEDURE.

SINGLE PAIL SHIPMENT WAS LOADED ON THE FLOOR BEHIND A PALLET OF OTHER FREIGHT. AT TIME OF DELIVERY, DRIVER DISCOVERED THAT THE PAIL HAD FALLEN OVER AND STRUCK THE PALLET, PUTTING A DENT IN THE PAIL. LEAKAGE WAS COMING FROM A CRACK IN THE DENT. CONSIGNEE ACCEPTED DELIVERY WITH AN EXCEPTION NOTATION.

TOTE ARRIVED FROM AT ON TRAILER 208053. FLOOR OF TRAILER HAD SPILLAGE ALL OVER. TRAILER HAD BOTH TOTE AND DRUMS. HAD TO TAKE OF TRAILER TO SEE WHICH ONE WAS LEAKING. WHEN DETERMINED, CHEMTREC WAS CALLED AND INFO WAS GIVEN TO THEM. THEY CONTACTED SHIPPER AND SHIPPER ARRANGED TO HAVE WASTE MANAGEMENT COME TO DAYTON TERMINAL TO CLEAN UP SPILLAGE AND TO TRANSFER TO ANOTHER TOTE. THAT TOTE WAS RETURNED TO SHIPPER.

column168: A FORMALDEHYDE (10%) DRUM WAS LOADED ON THE TRUCK. THEN THE TRUCK WAS TRAVELING TO IT'S NEXT STOP. WHILE THE DRIVER WAS LOADING THE TRUCK, HE NOTICED A LEAKING DRUM FROM THE PREVIOUS STOP. column168: ON OCTOBER 27, 1998, AT APPROXIMATELY 1000 HOURS, KCS CREW WAS SWITCHING A LOADED TANK CAR, NUMBER GATX52692, LOADED WITH CORROSIVE LIQUID NOS IN THE TENNECO PACKAGING PLANT LOCATED AT COUNCE, TN WHEN DURING A COUPLING EVENT, TWENTY TO THIRTY GALLONS OF THE TANK CARS CONTENTS RELEASED FROM A DEFECTIVE AND IMPROPERLY SECURED DOME LID SEAL WHEN THE MATERIAL RELEASED FROM THE TANK CAR, IF SPRAYED OUT, HITTING A KCS EMPLOYEE ON HIS BACK SIDE. THE EMPLOYEE SUSTAINED EXPOSURE TO HIS RIGHT LEG (FROM ABOVE HIS KNEE TO HIS ANKLE), LEFT HEEL AND ANKLE AND BOTH BUTTOCKS. THE EMPLOYEE WAS IMMEDIATELY RINSED OFF WITH WATER AND TAKEN TO THE MAGNOLIA REGIONAL HOSPITAL, CORINTH, MS AT THE HOSPITAL THE EMPLOYEE RECEIVED AND ADDITIONAL SHOWER, WAS TREATED WITH KENOLOG (A STEROID). BANDAGE WERE PLACED ON THE EFFECTED AREAS,  AND HE WAS GIVEN A PRESCRIPTION FOR PAIN (LORTAB). THE EMPLOYEE WAS RELEASED FROM THE HOSPITAL AND INSTRUCTED TO RETURN FOR A FOLLOW UP EXAMINATION. THE TANK CAR WAS BEING SWITCHED IN THE PLANT ONLY, AND WAS NOT BEING OFFERED FOR TRANSPORTATION . THE TENNECO PACKAGING PLANT (RESPONSIBLE PARTY) WAS NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED TO THE RELEASE. TENNECO ALSO INDICATED THAT ADDITIONAL STEPS HAVE BEEN TAKEN TO PROPERLY SECURE TANK CARS IN THE FUTURE.

THE SHIPPER (RESPONSIBLE PARTY) WAS IMMEDIATELY NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED TO THE INCIDENT SCENE MAKING NECESSARY REPAIRS TO THE DEFECTIVE DOME LID GASKET AND PROVIDING FOR DECONTAMINATION. UPON COMPLETION OF THE REPAIRS AND DECONTAMINATION, THE TANK CAR WAS THEN RELEASED FOR DESTINATION.

column168: AT THE SEA-LAND BARBOUR'S CUT TERMINAL FACILITY IN HOUSTON, CONTAINER GSTU264998 WAS OBSERVED TO HAVE WHITE RESIDUE ON THE DOOR ON OCTOBER 26, 1998 AT APPROXIMATELY 15:10 HOURS.  THE CONTAINER WAS STOPPED FROM GOING OUT OF THE TERMINAL FACILITY.  THE MATERIAL IN THE CONTAINER WAS IDENTIFIED TO BE SODIUM HYDROXIDE, DRY, CLASS 8, UN 1823, PACKING GROUP II, PACKED IN BAGS.  THE PORT OF HOUSTON FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS NOTIFIED, AND THE CONTAINER WAS TAKEN TO AN ISOLATED AREA.  THE DOOR WAS OBSERVED TO BE PARTIALLY OPEN.  THE FIRE DEPARTMENT OPENED THE RIGHT DOOR PART WAY, AND THE SOLID BEADS OF MATERIAL BEGAN POURING TO THE CONCRETE GROUND FROM THE BAGS THAT WERE LYING AGAINST THE DOOR.  THE CONTAINER DOOR WAS CLOSED.  THE SHIPPER ENICHEM WAS NOTIFIED, AND THE SHIPPER RETAINED THE SERVICES OF A HAZARDOUS MATERIAL CLEAN-UP CONTRACTOR.  THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER ASSIGNED A REPORT NUMBER 461425, WHEN THEY WERE CONTACTED AT 15:58 HOURS.  THE PORT OF HOUSTON POLICE AND TNRCC WERE ALSO NOTIFIED.  DUE TO THE TIME OF THE DAY, AND THE WEATHER CONDITIONS FURTHER ACTION ON THE CONTAINER WAS DELAYED FOR DAYLIGHT.  THE CONTRACTOR CLEANED THE SPILLED MATERIAL (APPROXIMATELY 25 POUNDS) ON THE CONCRETE GROUND.  DURING CLEAN-UP ONE PERSONNEL FROM THE CONTRACTOR'S FIRM HAD COME IN CONTACT WITH SODIUM HYDROXIDE FLAKE IN THE EYE.  THE PERSON WAS TAKEN TO THE HOSPITAL AND DISCHARGED THE SAME EVENING.  ON 10/27/98, A COMPREHENSIVE CLEANUP WAS STARTED BY STRIPPING THE CONTAINER.  ALL PALLETS IN GOOD CONDITION WERE DECONTAMINATED FOR RELOADING.  DAMAGED BAGS OF MATERIAL WERE REMOVED, THE PALLETS WERE RELOADED, RE-WRAPPED AND SECURED.  ON 10/28/98, THE PALLETS WERE RELOADED IN TO A NEW CONTAINER SEAU222634 FOR TRANSPORTATION TO FINAL DESTINATION.  THE AREA WAS DECONTAMINATED.  CONTAINER GSTU264998 WAS DECONTAMINATED, THE FLOOR REMOVED AND WAS DELIVERED BACK TO SEA-LAND.  CAUSE AND CORRECTIVE ACTION:  IMPROPER LOADING, BLOCKING AND BRACING IS THE MOST PROBABLE CAUSE.  IT IS POSSIBLE THAT PRODUCT SMOLDERED DURING THE VOYAGE, BECAUSE SOOT WAS OBSERVED ON THE CONTAINER DOOR, FLOOR, THE DUNNAGE AND PALLETS.  CONSIGNEE IN THE US IS FOLLOWING UP WITH SHIPPER IN ITALY TO PROPERLY LOAD THE CARGO AND BLOCK AND BRACE THE LOAD. SEA-LAND WILL PURSUE THIS ISSUE WITH THE CONSIGNEE/SHIPPER TO TAKE APPROPRIATE MEASURES TO PREVENT RECURRENCE.

column168: A WAREHOUSEMAN WAS INSPECTING A PRE-LOADED TRAILER AND NOTICED THAT A WRANGLER BAG HAD LEAKED APPROXIMATELY THREE GALLONS OF MATERIAL. THE WAREHOUSEMAN USED ABSORBENT PADS TO ABSORB THE MATERIAL, OPENED THE WRANGLER BAG AND ABSORBED AND RECLAIMED OTHER LIQUIDS AND PLACED ALL THE ABSORBED MATERIAL INTO A 55-GALLON OVERPACK.  THIS SPILL GENERATED APPROXIMATELY 40 POUNDS OF WASTE.  THE ABSORBED MATERIAL, AND THE ORIGINAL WASTE, WILL BE TRANSPORTED TO THE SAFETY-KLEEN FACILITY AT 3700 LAGRANGE ROAD, SMITHFIELD, KENTUCKY 40068 FOR DISPOSAL.  THE WAREHOUSEMAN WAS COUNSELED TO CHECK INCOMING SHIPMENTS OF WRANGLER BAS TO ENSURE THERE ARE NO LIQUIDS.  THE GENERATOR WAS ALSO CONTACTED AND INFORMED THAT LIQUID WASTE SHOULD NOT BE LOADED INTO THESE WRANGLER BAGS.

THE DRIVER OF THE TANKER BEGAN BOTTOM LOADING HIS VEHICLE AND LEFT THE IMMEDIATE ARE TO PERFORM AN ERRAND.  DURING HIS ABSENCE THE VEHICLE OVERFLOWED, APPROXIMATELY 300 GALLONS OF MATERIAL WAS SPILLED ONTO AN ASPHALT PARKING LOT.  SAFETY-KLEEN PERSONNEL IN THE VICINITY RESPONDED TO THE SPILL BY PLACING EARTH BERMS AND ABSORBENT BOOMS AROUND IT TO CONTAIN THE SPILL IN THE PARKING LOT.  A COMMERCIAL EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR WAS CONTACTED AND CAME IN AND DRUMMED UP THE MATERIAL.  ANOTHER COMMERCIAL CONTRACTOR WAS HIRED TO EXCAVATE THE CONTAMINATED SOIL AND ASPHALT FOR DISPOSAL AT A LICENSED DISPOSAL FACILITY.  THIS  SPILL GENERATED APPROXIMATELY 5000 POUNDS OF LIQUID WASTE THAT WAS TRANSPORTED TO THE SAFETY-KLEEN FACILITY AT 581 MILLIKEN DR SE, HEBRON, OH 43025 FOR RECYCLING.  THE CONTAMINATED SOIL AND ASPHALT IS IN THE PROCESS OF BEING REMOVED AND IS CURRENTLY STAGED ON SITE FOR REMOVAL TO A TREATMENT AND DISPOSAL FACILITY.

column168: A WAREHOUSEMAN INSPECTING A PALLET OF TRANSIT DRUMS DISCOVERED THAT A DEFECTIVE BUNG ON A 16 GALLON CONTAINER ALLOWED APPROXIMATELY 24 OUNCES OF MATERIAL TO LEAK ONTO THE WAREHOUSE FLOOR.  THE WAREHOUSE ABSORBED THE MATERIAL AND PLACED THE LEAKING DRUM AND THE ABSORBED MATERIAL ONTO A 30 GALLON OVERPACK.  THIS LEAK GENERATED APPROXIMATELY FIVE POUNDS OF WASTE.  THE ORIGINAL WASTE AND THE ABSORBED MATERIAL WILL BE SHIPPED TO THE SAFETY-KLEEN FACILITY AT 581 MILLIKEN DR SE, HEBRON OH 43025 FOR RECYCLING.   THE WAREHOUSEMAN WAS BRIEFED TO CLOSELY INSPECT INCOMING CONTAINERS FOR LEAKS TO AVOID SIMILAR FUTURE INCIDENTS.

THE DRIVER WAS PREPARING TO LOAD A SHIPMEN THAT HAD BEEN IN TEMPORARY STORAGE WHEN HE NOTICED THAT ONE OF THE DRUMS HAD A LOOSE BUNG HOLE COVER THAT ALLOWED APPROXIMATELY 4 OUNCES OF MATERIAL TO LEAK.  THE DRIVER ABSORBED THE LEAKING MATERIAL WITH VERMICULITE AND PLACED THE ABSORBED MATERIAL AND LEAKING DRUM INTO AN 85- GALLON OVERPACK.  THIS LEAK RESULTED IN THE GENERATION OF ONE POUND OF WASTE.  THE ABSORBED MATERIAL AND THE DRUM IN THE OVERPACK WILL BE TRANSPORTED TO THE SAFETY-KLEEN FACILITY AT 1722 COOPER CREEK ROAD, DENTON, TEXAS 76208 FOR TREATMENT.  WAREHOUSE PERSONNEL WERE COUNSELED TO CHECK DRUM CLOSURES MORE FREQUENTLY TO FIND LEAKERS.

THE DRIVER LOADED THE WASTE INTO THE DRUMS AND WAS MOVING THEM TO HIS VEHICLE WHEN HE NOTICED THAT ONE OF THE DRUMS HAD A PINHOLE LEAK AND LEAKED APPROXIMATELY THREE GALLONS OF MATERIAL ONTO THE ASPHALT PARKING LOT.  THE DRIVER USED ABSORBENT MATS TO CLEANUP THE SPILLED MATERIAL.  HE USED ABSORBENT PADS AND THE LEAKING DRUM WAS PLACED INTO A 55-GALLON DRUM OVERPACK.   THIS SPILL GENERATED APPROXIMATELY 40 POUNDS OF WASTE THAT WAS SENT, ALONG WITH THE ORIGINAL WASTE, TO THE SAFETY-KLEEN FACILITY AT 633 E 138TH STREET, DOLTON IL 60419 AND IS PENDING FINAL SHIPMENT TO A SAFETY-KLEEN TSDF.  THE DRIVER WAS COUNSELED TO CHECK DRUMS FOR LEAKS IMMEDIATELY AFTER LOADING MATERIAL IN THEM TO AVOID FUTURE INCIDENTS SUCH AS THIS.

Leak was discovered at drop yard while waiting for a "border broker carrier", to pick up and take into Mexico. Product soaked through the wood floor in the middle under-carriage of the trailer. Report was called in to Schneider. Schneider hired a clean up crew (code 3) who overpacked the leaky 55 gallon drum. The spill was only five gallons and spread over a 3 x 5 foot area. The bottom rung of a drum next to the leaker abraded the metal and the ring of the leaking drum and caused a scrap that turned into a small hole. Ashland Chemical arranged to have the overpacked drum returned to their facility in Cleveland, Ohio by L & L Carrier- Yellow Freight.

column168: Driver of the vehicle was not attentive and possible speed contributed to the accident. Single vehicle lost control and overturned causing contents to spill. Driver severely injured, paralyzed. Driver did not come in contact with any hazards.

Upon arrival at the facility, the unloading crew opened the trailer doors and they noticed less than one cup of product around one drum. Upon inspection of the drum, they noticed some seepage from the bottom side of the drum. The drum had a small crease where the fork on the forklift damaged the drum. The customer unloaded the trailer and the secondary containment floor in the trailer.

BNSF responder noticed an ammonia odor emanating from area of standing residue tank cars in yard track. Further investigation revealed loose packing gland nut on gauging device of tank car, which the responder tightened. Car was released to destination. Shipper to be notified of incident for their review and remedial action plan.

Switch crew noticed product sloshed out of manway cover when switching car and movement stopped. Responder opened manway cover and gasket that was improperly installed fell inside car. Replacement gasket material applied. Minimal product loss and exposed product evaporated. Car was released to destination. Shipper to be notified of incident for their review.

Northtown yard train master reported an ammonia smell in bowl tracks. BNSF responders reported finding tank car with a vapor leak at the thermometer well. Car was isolated and Farmland responders replaced O-rings on thermometer well stem that wouldn't hold pressure. Car was released to destination after Farmland finalized repairs. As a precautionary measure, a BNSF switchman was taken to a local hospital; treated and released back to work. Farmland Industries to be contacted for remedial action plan.

BNSF car man reported an ammonia smell in North town yard departure track containing nine empty residue tank cars. BNSF responder investigating found car leaking at safety relief valve (SRV) and car isolated in yard. Contractor made repairs to the SRV cap and o-rings; and tested seal. Car released to destination. As a precautionary measure, car man taken to a local hospital, treated and released back to work. Shipper will be notified on this incident for their review.

Outbound truck drive noticed container leaking. Container was isolated and BNSF responders investigated. One drum was found leaking at a lower rolling loop that cracked. This condition was either caused by pre-loading or loading activity. Drum was placed in salvage container and spillage was cleaned. BNSF damage prevention team will contact shipper for corrective action.

Car inspectors working train reported an odor emanating from tank car. BNSF responders investigating reported loose manway cover bolts and vapor leaking from top operated bottom outlet valve (TOBOV). Manway bolts were tightened and TOBOV packing gland nut tightened 1 1/2 turns and car released to its destination. Shipper will be notified on this incident for future corrective action.

At approximately 1630 hours, Sunday, October 18, 1998, at Milepost 204.0, on the Saint Louis Line in Pierron, Illinois, Conrail Train TRIN8 derailed thirty two (32) cars. Provided is a list of four (4) tank cars containing hazardous material involved in the derailment. Appropriate notification made. ACFX 80971, containing residue picolines lost what is estimated to be less than five gallons. The tank car sustained damage to the top fittings on the car. The manway cover bolts sheared off, safety valve relief packed with dirt and other fittings and safety railing equipment bent, broken or missing. Also part of the top of the tank car was crushed inward, holed and cracked (approximately 4-6 feet long and 2-4 feet wide). The right side of the car was holed and cracked approximately mid-tank (low on tank). The tank car was cleaned and purged and cut up on site. KCCX 2677, containing sulfuric acid, lost what is estimated to be less than fifteen gallons. The manway fill hole and liquid line cap were impacted and the defective cap for the safety vent assembly was torn off of the car. This car also sustained numerous dents, scores and gouges to both sides and ends but none cut into any weld seams. The commodity was transferred into five cargo tanks. The tank car was cleaned and purged and cut up on site. ECUX 408129, containing residue elevated temperature, liquid n.o.s., was derailed and did not release any product. Tank car was okayed for transportation and forwarded to destination. PLCX 221745, containing residue elevated temperature liquid, flammable n.o.s., was derailed upright in line and did not release any product. The tank car was cleaned and purged and cut up on site. Heritage Environmental, an environmental remediation contractor handled the clean up. The cause of the derailment was a broken wheel on the NATX 25440.

There was no indication of a problem with the hose before or during the off-loading of the first barge. column168: Loose packing gland nut on the gauging rod, GATX 97939, October 20, 1998, Albany division. At approximately 0940 hours, Tuesday, October 20, 1998, at Conrail's Gangs Mill yard in Painted Post, NY, a Conrail conductor noticed an odor emanating from tank car GATX 97939 containing ammonia anhydrous. Appropriate notification was made. At approximately 1230 hours, a representative from the consignee, Liquefied products arrived at the site, examined the car and determined that it had loose packing gland nut on the gauging rod. Repairs were made by the general manager of Liquefied products who tightened the packing gland nut on the gauging rod. At 1330 hours, the tank car was secured, okayed for transportation and sent to destination.

Product released from the safety relief valve, ACFX 84518, October 31, 1998, Philadelphia Division. At approximately 1700 hours, Saturday, October 31, at Conrail's Abrams yard in King of Prussia, PA, Conrail's director of haz mat and haz mat field service manager discovered product residue covering approximately 75% of tank car ACFX 84518, containing sodium hydroxide solution, No product was found on the ground. Appropriate notification was made. They examined the tank car and determined that the product released from the safety release valve. All valves, fittings and closures were inspected and no further exceptions were noted. On Monday, November 2, 1998, React, an environmental remediation contractor arrived on the site and externally cleaned the tank car. The tank car was okayed for transportation and sent to destination.

column168: THE SHIPMENT WAS BEING PROCESSED DURING THE OUTBOUND PACKAGE SORT WHEN THE DAMAGE/LEAKAGE OCCURRED.  THE SHIPMENT HAD APPARENTLY BEEN DAMAGE/DROPPED IN HANDLING RESULTING IN LEAKAGE AND ODOR.  THE PACKAGE WAS ISOLATED, OPENED AND EXAMINED TO REVEAL FIVE METAL CANS OF AN UNDETERMINED QUANTITY.  THE LID SEAL HAD FAILED ON ONE OF THE CANS ALLOWING THE RELEASE OF THE MATERIAL.  THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED AND THE SHIPMENT WAS PLACED INTO A SALVAGE DRUM AN MSDS OBTAINED FROM THE PRODUCT MANUFACTURER AND THE CHARACTERISTICS SHOWN ON THE DOCUMENT INDICATED THAT THE MATERIAL DID EXHIBIT FLAMMABLE PROPERTIES THAT WERE NOT ACCOUNTED FOR.  THERE WERE NO HAZMAT MARKINGS OF LABELS EXHIBITED ON THE OUTER PACKAGE NOR WAS THERE A SHIPPER'S DECLARATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS IN EVIDENCE WITH THE SHIPMENT.  THE SHIPMENT WAS HELD PENDING NOTIFICATION TO FAA FOR INVESTIGATION.

PACKAGE FELL OFF OF A WOOD PALLET ONTO THE GROUND,  NEAR THE AREA WHERE THIS WAS TO BE LOADED INTO A CONTAINER.  A FORKLIFT DRIVER FAILED TO SEE THE PACKAGE AND RAN OVER IT.  THE AREA WAS CLEARED AND THE DANGEROUS GOODS RESPONSE TEAM WAS CALLED TO THE HEAVYWEIGHT AREA.  THE AREA WAS BLOCKED OFF WHILE THE CONTACT WAS MADE TO THE FEDEX AREA RADIATION PHYSICS CONSULTANT  DR. ROY PARKER.  HE CONTACTED THE LOCAL STATE OF TN RADIOLOGICAL HEALTH OFFICE OF THE INCIDENT.  ALAN GREWE, AREA MGR, ARRIVED ON THE SCENE WITH TWO ASSISTANTS TO SURVEY THE AFFECTED AREAS.  UNDER THE DIRECTION OF THESE PARTIES, THE AREA WAS IRRIGATED IN A CONTROLLED ENVIRONMENT WITH THE WATER CAPTURED.  FURTHER SURVEYS REVEALED THE RADIATION LEVELS OF THE AFFECTED AREA WERE DECREASING.  FURTHER EFFORTS WITH WATER REDUCED THESE AREAS AS WELL.  THE AFFECTED AREA (SPOTS) WERE THEN REMOVED AND PLACED IN SALVAGE DRUMS.  THE ASPHALT WAS PHYSICALLY REMOVED FROM THESE EFFECTED AREAS FOR CONTAINMENT.  THE VEHICLE INVOLVED WAS LOCATED AND THE TIRES ON ONE SIDE WERE REMOVED. NUMEROUS EMPLOYEES THAT WERE IN THE AFFECTED AREA DID GO TO THE HOSPITAL TO HAVE THEIR THYROID CHECKED, AND THE RESULTS OF THE TEST STATED THESE PEOPLE WERE NOT AFFECTED OR EXPOSED BODILY.  AN OUTSIDE CONTRACTOR WAS CONTACTED TO ALSO COME OUT AND SURVEY AND AFFECTED AREA AND TO OBSERVE THE OPERATION TO BE SURE THERE WAS NO FURTHER RISK OF SPREADING ANY CONTAMINATED AREA.  THIS INCIDENT WAS REPORTED TO THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER AND THE INCIDENT IS UNDER NUMBER 460987.

SINCE THE LOADING FACILITY DID NOT HAVE A PAD OR CONTAINMENT DEVICE IT WENT ON THE GROUND. IT APPEARS THE METAL WAS ATTACKED BY ACID AND WHEN IT GOT WEAK ENOUGH THE PRESSURE FROM THE INSIDE PUSHED THE RUBBER LINING THROUGH THE WEAK SPOT. THE EXTERIOR OF THE CARGO TANK WAS PAINTED WITH A BLACK RUBBERIZED PAINT IN THAT AREA TO PREVENT ACID FROM CONTACTING THE MATAL. THE ACID DESTROYED THE MATAL BETWEEN THE BLACK PAINT AND HTE RUBBER LINING AND WAS NOT DETECTED AND MAY NOT HAVE BEEN VISABLE PRIOR TO FAILURE.

During the unloading process, the product hose used to discharge product from cargo tanker into customer's tank suddenly ruptured and allowed spillage to occur. The driver immediately closed the valves and stopped the unloading-spillage. The spillage was contained in the customer's containment pad and soda ash was used to neutralize the product.

During unloading, the driver was asked to stop the unloading process to enable the customer's tractor trailer to be moved at the scene. Therefore, driver had to move and/ or clean out product from his discharge hose prior to the movement of the customer's tank. In doing so, back pressure from customer's tank caused product to spray out. To prevent future occurrence, driver will be instructed not to allow the interruption of the unloading process to occur prior to emptying cargo tankers.

HIS WHEELS CAME OFF THE ROAD AND WHEN HE SWERVED TO GET BACK ON THE ROAD THE TRUCK ROLLED OVER.  DUE TO IMPACT THE TANK RUPTURED AND CAUSED THE SPILL OF DIESEL.  ALL ENVIRONMENTAL AUTHORITIES WERE CALLED.  CLEAN UP IS IN PROCESS. DRIVER WAS INJURED WITH ONLY MINOR CUTS AND BRUISES.

column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: DRIVER STATED HE SWERVED TO AVOID HITTING A DEER.  LOST CONTROL OF VEHICLE AND OVERTURNED SPILLING ALMOST THE ENTIRE LOAD.  ALL ENVIRONMENTAL AGENCIES WERE CONTACTED.  CLEAN UP IS IN PROCESS. TANKER WAS REMOVED FROM THE SCENE.  DRIVER WAS INJURED WITH ONLY CUTS AND BRUISES.
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column168: 1 ROLL & 5 BOXES WAS WRAPPED TOGETHER.  WAS ON TOP OF BANDED PLT FELL OFF OF PLT ON TOP OF DRUMS 2 BOTTLES IN BOXES BUSTED OPEN LEAKED OUT.

UPON RETURNING TO THE DOCK, A DRIVER DISCOVERED THAT THE TOP OF THE SUPER SACK HAD COME OPEN DURING TRANSPORT AND SPILLED ABOUT 400 POUNDS OF SLUDGE (A SOLID) IN THE VAN TRAILER.  THE SPILL MATERIAL WAS RECOVERED INTO A DRUM AND THE SUPER SACK WAS OVERPACKED INTO A BULK BIN WITH A LID.  BOTH THE DRUM AND OVERPACKED BAG WERE THEN SHIPPED TO THE DESIGNATED FACILITY ON THE ATTACHED MANIFEST BY TRANSPORTER 2 OTHER BULK PACKAGING FOR SLUDGE IS BEING INVESTIGATED FOR PRACTICALITY AND PERFORMANCE.  IF A BETTER ALTERNATIVE IS IDENTIFIED, IT WILL BE RECOMMENDED TO THE GENERATOR FOR USE.
CUSTOMER HAD UNLOADED TRAILER AND ADVISED OUR DRIVER.  DRIVER PULLED HOSE OFF OF CUSTOMER'S FITTING & APPROXIMATELY 30 GALLONS OF PRODUCT SPILLED OUT.
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column168: AN EDWARDS OIL COMPANY DRIVER WAS FILLING THE #1 DIESEL FUEL TANK AT THE LUCKY SEVEN GENERAL STORE IN HIBBING, MN (OWNED BY EDWARDS OIL CO).  WHEN THE TANK WAS FULL, THE FILL PIPE FLAP SNAPPED SHUT AND THE FILLER HOSE JUMPED OUT ONTO THE FILL PIPE.  THE OIL RESIDUE IN THE FILLER HOSE SPILLED ONTO THE CONCRETE PAD SURROUNDING THE FILL PIPE.  THE SPILL WAS SOAKED UP IMMEDIATELY WITH PADS, WHICH WERE THEN PUT IN PLASTIC BAGS FOR PROPER DISPOSAL.

column42: AEROSOLS, FLAMMABLE, (EACH NOT EXCEEDING 1 L CAPACITY)
column168: THIS BOX WAS OBSERVED FALLING OFF A CONVEYOR BELT TO THE GROUND, STRIKING THE TOP OF THE BOX.  THE SPILL CLEAN UP PERSONNEL WERE NOTIFIED AND THEY DISCOVERED THAT 2 OF THE INNER METAL AEROSOL CANS HAD DISCHARGED INSIDE THE BOX.  THE PLASTIC PROTECTIVE CAPS WERE KNOCKED OFF THE CANS WHEN THE PACKAGE FELL.  THE CONTENTS WERE PLACED IN A SALVAGE DRUM, AND THE SHIPPER WAS CONTACTED FOR A DISPOSITION.  THE SHIPMENT WAS TO MOVE ON TO CONSIGNEE PER INSTRUCTIONS FROM SHIPPER.

PACKAGE WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING DURING THE SORTING OPERATION. PACKAGE WAS NOTICED TO HAVE AN ODOR AND STAIN ON THE OUTER BOX.  THE BOX  WAS ISOLATED FROM THE OTHERS AND THE SPILL PERSONNEL WERE NOTIFIED.  UPON INSPECTION OF THE CONTENTS, THEY DISCOVERED THAT ONE OF THE METAL CANS HAD A LOOSE CLOSURE.  CONTENTS WERE PLACED IN A SALVAGE DRUM AND THE SHIPPER WAS CONTACTED FOR DISPOSITION OF THIS PACKAGE.

PACKAGE WAS FOUND TO BE LEAKING AFTER THE BOX HAD BEEN STRUCK BY THE WHEEL OF A BAGGAGE CART.  THE PACKAGE WAS BEING MOVED INSIDE A BAGGAGE CART, AND HAD FALLEN FROM THE BEHIND THE CURTAIN AND TO THE GROUND UNDERNEATH THE TIRE.  THE SPILL CLEANUP PERSONNEL WERE NOTIFIED AND THEY INSPECTED THE DAMAGED PACKAGE.  IT WAS FOUND THAT ONE OF THE 4 METAL CANS INSIDE THE BOX HAD LEAKED AROUND THE CLOSURE.  THE PACKAGE WAS PLACED IN A SALVAGE DRUM AND THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENT.

PACKAGE WAS NOTICED TO HAVE A STRONG ODOR DURING THE SORTING OPERATION.  THIS PACKAGE WAS ISOLATED FROM THE OTHERS, AND THE SPILL CLEANUP PERSONNEL WERE NOTIFIED.  UPON FURTHER INSPECTION, IT WAS NOTIFIED THAT THE INNER CLOSURE WAS NOT SECURE AND THERE WAS A SMALL AMOUNT OF THE CONTENTS ON THE METAL CAN.  CONTENTS WERE PLACED IN A SALVAGE DRUM, AND THE SHIPPER WAS CONTACTED REGARDING A DISPOSITION.

column58: Auxiliary Valve; Bottom Outlet Valve; Piping or Fittings
column168: LOOSE TOP OPERATED BOTTOM OUTLET PACKING GLAND NUT, LOOSE TOP OPERATING BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE HANDLE & LOOSE MANWAY COVER SECUREMENT BOLT, GATX 46168, OCTOBER 14, 1998, ALBANY DIVISION.  AT APPROXIMATELY 2220 HOURS, MONDAY, OCTOBER 14, 1998, AT CONRAIL'S SELKIRK YARD IN SELKIRK, NY, A CONRAIL CAR INSPECTOR NOTED PRODUCT LEAKING FROM THE BOTTOM OF TANK CAR GATX 46168 CONTAINING PETROLEUM DISTILLATES, NOS.  APPROPRIATE NOTIFICATION MADE.  AT APPROXIMATELY 2235 HOURS, CONRAIL'S HAZARDOUS MATERIAL FIELD SERVICE MANAGER RESPONDED TO THE SCENE AND INVESTIGATION REVEALED A LOOSE TOP OPERATED BOTTOM OUTLET PACKING GLAND NUT, LOOSE TOP OPERATING BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE HANDLE & LOOSE MANWAY COVER SECUREMENT BOLT.  REPAIRS WERE MADE BY CONRAIL'S HAZARDOUS MATERIAL FIELD SERVICE MANAGER WHO TIGHTENED THE TOP OPERATING BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE HANDLE, SECURED THE TOP OPERATED BOTTOM OUTLET PACKING GLAND NUT, TIGHTENED THE MANWAY COVER SECUREMENT BOLT AND CLEANED THE SPILLED AREA.  AT APPROXIMATELY 0025 HOURS, TUESDAY, OCTOBER 15, 1998, THE TANK CAR WAS SECURED, APPROVED FOR TRANSPORTATION AND SENT TO DESTINATION.

OUR MAN WAS UNLOADING THE TRAILER AND WHILE DOING SO OBSERVED THIS SHIPMENT.  THE CARTON WAS TURNED OVER AND LEAK OUT FROM THE TOP ONTO THE COUNTER.  WE CONTACTED THE OXYGEN TERMINAL AND GENERAL OFFICE. WHO ADOISED THE SUPERVISOR HAT TO DO THIS COULD HAVE BEEN PREVENTED AND WAS STACKED DOWN AND DUNNAGE USED.

column168: DRIVER WAS TRAVELING EAST BOUND ON OBRERO DR.IN MISSION VIEJO.HE APPROACHED JERONIMO RD. AND PROCEEDED TO MAKE A RIGHT TURN. HE FELT A BUMP IN THE BACK OF HIS VEHICLE FROM A PICK-UP TRUCK WHICH HAS RUN UNDER THE LEFT SIDE OF THE TRAILER. THE HEADER BAR SHEARED AS DESIGNED AND INTERNAL VALVE SHUT OFF CORRECTLY. LESS THAN ONE GALLON OF PRODUCT SPILLED.

UPON ARRIVAL AT TERMINAL THE DRIVER OPENED THE TRAILER DOORS TO INSPECT THE LOAD AND HE NOTICED A SMALL PUDDLE AROUND THE ONE DRUM. UPON INSPECTING THE DRUM HE NOTICED A SMALL AREA MADE BY THE FORKS ON THE FORKLIFT AND TO THE FLEXING OF THE DRUM IT STARTED DEEPING.THE DRIVER OVERPACKED THE DRUM AND CLEARED UP THE SPILLED PRODUCT. THE TRAILER HAS SECONDARY CONTAINMENT SO NO PRODUCT ESCAPE INTO THE ENVIRONMENT.

A SAFETY-KLEEN DRIVER WAS MOVING A 16 GALLON DRUM FROM A WASTE STORAGE AREA TO THE TRUCK WHEN IT FELL OFF HIS HAND TRUCK. WHEN IT HIT THE GROUND THE LID POPPED OFF AND EIGHT GALLONS OF MATERIAL SPILLED. THE DRIVER USED ABSORBENTS TO CLEAN UP THE SPILL AND CONTAINERIZED THIS MATERIAL FOR DISPOSAL. THIS SPILL GENERAL APPROXIMATELY 160 POUNDS OF WASTE THAT WAS TRANSPORTED, ALONG WITH THE ORIGINAL WASTE, TO THE SAFETY-KLEEN FACILITY AT 2130 EAST GRAUWYLER, IRVING,TEXAS FOR RECYCLING. THE DRIVER WAS COUNSELED TO USE MORE CARE WHEN LOADING CONTAINERS IN THE FUTURE TO AVOID SIMILAR INCIDENTS.

AT END OF UNLOADED PROCESS, THE CUSTOMER STORAGE TANK OVERFLOWED. THE CUSTOMER STORAGE TANK ALSO SUSTAINED A STRUCTURAL FAILER AND BECAME "FOOTBALL SHAPED" FROM ITS ORIGINAL CUBICAL SHAPE WITH INSULATION AND OUTER SHIELDING. THE BOWING OF THE INNER STORAGE TANK CAUSED THE OUTER SHIELDING TO BECOME DISARRAYED AND/OR DETACHED AT SOME POINTS ON THE OUTER SURFACE. THERE WAS NO DAMAGE TO THE TANK DID NOT HAVE SUFFICIENT SPACE PRIOR TO DELIVERY AND SOME PROBLEM EXISTED WITH STORAGE TANK VENTING SYSTEM. THE CONSIGNEE MANAGEMENT BELIEVE THAT THE PROBLEM WAS CAUSED BY THE PRODUCT ARRIVING IN TWO SEPARATE COMPARTMENT TRAILER. THERE IS NO AGREEMENT AS OF 11/20/1998. AT TIME OF SPILLAGE, THERE WERE NO INJURIES, AND NO PRODUCT REACHED ANY WATERWAYS.

DURING UNLOADING THE CARRIER, COMMODITY DISCHARGE HOSE RUPTURED, WITH LOSS OF PRODUCT. SPILL CONTAINED AND CLEANED-UP BY FACILITY PERSONNEL. DISCHARGE HOSE WAS REPLACED AND DELIVERY COMPLETED WITHOUT FURTHER INCIDENT.

AIR VALVE WAS LEFT OPEN BY DRIVER AND THE OUTLET WAS NOT CAPPED. WHEN DRIVER PERFORMED SLOSH TEST AT SHIPPER. PRODUCT GOT INTO THE AIR LINE., EACH TIME DRIVER STARTED OR STOPPED IN PLANT, SOME PRODUCT DRIPPED ONTO ROADWAY. CARRIER SENT CLEANUP CONTRACTOR TO REMEDIATE PLANT DRIVERWAYS AND ROADS. THERE WERE NO INJURIES, ND NO PRODUCT REACHED ANY WATERWAYS.

DURING THE UNLOADING PROCESS, THE CUSTOMER'S TANK OVERFLOWED. THE STORAGE TANK HAS NO GUAGE ON IT. DRIVER HAD INFORMED SUPERVISOR PRIOR TO UNLOADING ABOUT THE QUANTITY ON THE TANK TRUCK. THAT SUPERVISOR HAD INDICATED THAT DRIVER WOULD BE INFORMED WHEN IT WAS TIME TO SHUT OFF THE UNLOADING. THE CUSTOMER TANK OVERFLOWED BEFORE ANYONE NOTIFIED DRIVER. NO PRODUCT REACHED ANY WATERWAY. CUSTOMER PERSONNEL CLEANED UP SPILL. THERE WERE NO INJURIES.

TRAILER WAS LOADED AND TRAVELED SUCCESSFULLY OVER THE 419 MILES SHIP LOCATION TO CUSTOMER WITH NO PROBLEMS. DRIVER POSITIONED TRAILER FOR UNLOADING AND WHEN HE OPENED INTERNAL VALVE OF TRAILER, THE PRODUCT BEGAN TO SPRAY FROM SEVERAL POINTS ON THE UNLOADING LINE. THE BOLTS WERE LOOSE IN MORE THAN ONE SPOT. DRIVER SHUT DOWN THE PROCEDURE AND ATTEMPTED TO TIGHTEN BOLTS. THIS WAS UNSECCESSFUL, AND THE UNIT WAS TAKEN OFF-SITE TO LOCAL TERMINAL OF ANOTHER TRUCKING COMPANY(MC KENZIE TANK LINES)FOR INSPECTION AND REPAIR. AFTER ADJUSTMENT, THE VEHICLE WAS BROUGHT BACK TO THE CUSTOMER AND UNLOADED. ALL SPILLED PRODUCT WAS CAPTURED IN CUSTOMER CONTAINMENT SYSTEM. NO MATERIAL REACHED ANY WATERWAYS.

SAFETY VALVE FROSTED OVER AND A SLIGHT VAPOR VENT DUE FROM HIGHER THAN NORMAL INTERNAL PRESSURE, UTLX80001, OCTOBER 31, 1998 PHILADELPHIA DIVISION. AT APPROXIMATELY 1530 HOURS, SATURDAYS OCTOBER 31, 1998 AT CONRAIL'S ABRAMS YARD IN KING PRUSSIA, PA, A CONRAIL CAR INSPECTOR NOTED VENTING FROM THE TOP OF TANK CAR UTLX 80001 CONTAINING ETHYLENE, REFRIGERATED LIQUID. APPROPRIATE NOTIFICATION MADE. AT APPROXIMATELY 1600 HOURS, CONRAIL'S MANAGER HAZARDOUS MATERIALS ARRIVED AT THE SITE. UPON FURTHER EXAMINATION OF THE TANK CAR, IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE SAFETY RELIEF VALVE WAS FROSTED OVER AND THERE WAS A SLIGHT VAPOR VENT DUE FROM HIGHER THAN NORMAL INTERNAL PRESSURE. ADDITIONALLY, A NANILA TAG WAS ATTACHED TO THE SAFETY VALVE, NOTING BAD VALVE VALVE LIFTS AT 30 POUNDS WITH NO DATE, LOCATION OR WRITER'S NAME SHOWN. MOVEMENT AUTHORITY OBTAINED BY THE SHIPPER THROUGH FRA. A VERBAL APPROVAL WAS GIVEN FROM THE FRA TO ALLOW THE CAR TO RETURN TO THE SHIPPER. THE TANK CAR WAS PLACED IN A SPECIAL TRAIN AND SENT BACK TO THE SHIPPER. THE CAR RETURNED TO SHIPPER'S ORIGINAL LOADING FACILITY ON NOVEMBER 1, 1998.

column168: PACKAGE WAS FOUND TO BE LEAKING DURING THE SORTING OPERATION AT THIS FACILITY.  THE PACKAGE HAD MOVED INCORRECTLY TO THIS LOCATION, AND IT WAS NOT TO BE DELIVERED IN THIS AREA.  THE PACKAGE HAD A STRONG ODOR AND WAS ISOLATED FROM ALL PERSONNEL AND THE MANAGER OPENED THE PACKAGE.  HE NOTICED THAT THE INNER BOX HAD A FLAMMABLE LIQUID LABEL, BUT THE OUTER BOX DID NOT HAVE ANY LABELS OR MARKINGS.  THIS PACKAGE WAS NOT SHIPPED WITH THE PROPER LABELING, MARKINGS, OR ANY DANGEROUS GOODS DECLARATION PAPERWORK.  THE MANAGER CALLED TO REPORT THIS LEAKING PACKAGE TO ME, AND I CONTACTED GREAT LAKES FAA DUTY OFFICER TO REPORT THIS PACKAGE.  I LATER SPOKE TO BOB CLATTERBUCK OF THE MSP/CASFO OFFICE, AND HE WAS TO INVESTIGATE THIS PACKAGE.  THE PACKAGE HAD BEEN ACCEPTED AS A NON-DANGEROUS GOODS, AND IT WAS MOVED ON FEDEX FIT 19K TO OUR IND HUB, AND THEN IT MOVED TO MKE-R ON FIT 1732.  AT MKE-R, THE PACKAGE WAS LOADED ON FIT 8763 TO IMT-A.  THE SHIPPER WAS CONTACTED, AND THEY FAXED A COPY OF THE MATERIAL SAFETY DATA SHEET FOR THIS PRODUCT.  PACKAGE IS HOLDING AT THIS FACILITY UNTIL INVESTIGATION IS COMPLETED.

At approximately 1215 hours, October 2, 1998, Donald R. Goode, the Apria Healthcare employee involved in the incident, was preparing to refill a patients oxygen concentrator at 4843 Atlanta Drive, San Diego, California. Goode mistakenly opened the check valve discharge hose without closing the main discharge valve. This resulted in the discharge of approximately 203 gallons of oxygen, refrigerated liquid onto the sidewalk and adjacent flower bed. The San Diego Fire Department and their Haz-mat incident response team responded. The haz-mat team closed the valve and thawed out the area with a water stream. Goode received out-patient treatment for a minor liquid burn and returned to duty. Damage was limited to minor plant damage. Good has been counseled in reference to the proper operation of the cargo tank. The incident is being reviewed for use as an in service training subject.

DSR KEN YOUNGBLOOD LOADED THIS SHIPMENT WITH LONG BLADES, UNAWARE HE HAD PUNCTURED THE BOX IN SKID WITH THE BLADES PUNCTURING TWO AND A HALF GALLON PAILS. THE TANK CAR WAS FOUND BY LOCAL RAILROAD FORCES AT LIVONIA YARD TO BE LEAKING ITS CONTENTS. THE LEAKAGE WAS A SMALL STREAM OF PRODUCT DOWN THE SIDE OF THE CAR FROM BENEATH THE PROTECTIVE COVER FOR THE TOP VALVES. THE CAR WAS SET POUT AND ISOLATED WITH OUT INCIDENT. UNION PACIFIC RAILROAD, DIRECTOR OF TERMINAL OPERATIONS AT LIVONIA, MR. B. W. WOOD ALL, NOTIFIED UPRR MANAGER OF ENVIRONMENTAL FIELD OPERATIONS, T. M. ROBINSON. UPON ARRIVAL ROBINSON FOUND THAT THE LEAKAGE HAD BEEN COMING FROM BETWEEN THE FLANGES OF THE EDUCTION PIPE AND THE LIQUID VALVE. THE FLANGES ARE SECURED BY FOUR BOLTS WITH NUTS, ONE OF THE NUTS COULD BE TURNED BY HAND AND TWO OTHERS NEEDED TIGHTENING AS WELL. ROBINSON SECURED THE FLANGES AND MADE THEM TOOL TIGHT. THE CAR WAS HELD IN ISOLATION FOR SEVERAL MORE HOURS TO VERIFY THAT HEAT (FROM THE DAY) INDUCED PRESSURE WOULD NOT CAUSE ADDITIONAL LEAKAGE. THERE WAS NO FURTHER LEAKAGE. ROBINSON SPOKE WITH MR. JIM MOBBERLY, SAFETY ENGINEER FOR ASHLAND CHEMICAL AND ADVISED MIM OF THE INCIDENT. MR. MOBBERLY FELT THE CAR WAS GOOD TO PROCEED TO DESTINATION. ADDITIONALLY, NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE VIA THE UPRR RISKS MANAGEMENT COMMUNICATIONS CENTER TO CHEMTREC, THE SHIPPER (ASHLAND CHEMICAL). THE LOUISIANA STATE POLICE, THE LOUISIANA DEPT. OF ENVIRONMENTAL QUALITY AND THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER. DIRECTOR WOODALL NOTIFIED THE POINTE COUPEE PARISH 911 CENTER.

DEAN C. COOPER, MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS CONTACTED BY THE ICTF SECURITY FORCES REPORTING A LEAKING INTERMODAL TANK.L MANAGER COOPER DROVE TO THE ICTF FACILITY AND LOCATED THE IM TANK IN GREEN ROW STALL #316. A SMALL POOL OF LIQUID, LESS THAN ONE GALLON, WAS LOCATED ON THE PAVEMENT AT THE REAR OF THE CHASSIS, DIRECTLY BELOW THE DISCHARGE VALVE OF THE IM TANK. INSPECTION OF THE IM TANK DEVELOPED THE LEAK WAS COMING FROM BEHIND THE VALVE COMPARTMENT AND WAS DRIPPING FROM THE JACKET LINER ONTO THE CHASSIS DECK PLATE, WHICH THEN ALLOWED THE PRODUCT TO TRAIL TO THE END OF THE PLATE AND DRIP ONTO THE PAVEMENT. A SAMPLE OF THE LIQUID WAS OBTAINED AND FIELD TESTED FOR PH WHICH SHOWED THE MATERIAL WAS ABOVE THE 12 RANGE, INDICATING IT WAS PRODUCT. AS THE LEAK APPEARED TO BE A SLOW, BUT ACTIVE DRIPPING, THE IM TANK WAS MOVED TO CURB SIDE AT THE CUSTOMS DOCK WHERE IT COULD BE ISOLATED AND CONTAINED. THE AREA IN THE ORIGINAL PARKING STALL WAS NEUTRALIZED AND CLEARED. CONTACT WAS MADE WITH THE BULKTAINER GROUP IN ST. LOUIS AND THEY WERE ADVISED THE IM TANK APPEARED TO HAVE FAILED AND THE CONTENTS WOULD REQUIRE TRANSLOADING. AS THE PRODUCT WAS SHIPPED BY UNION CARBIDE, THEIR LOCAL REPRESENTATIVE MADE ARRANGEMENTS TO COMPLETE THE TRANSLOAD OPERATION. BULKTAINER PROVIDED IM TANK, UPTU 660348, WHICH WAS DELIVERED Y CHEMICAL LEANAN TO THE ICTF. THE REPLACEMENT IM TANK WAS STENCILED AND PLACARDER, AND THE BILLING CORRECTED TO SHOW THE NEW VESSEL IDENTIFICATION NUMBER. THE RESIDUE IM TANK WILL BE PURGED AND HOPPED FOR INSPECTION. DUE TO THE MINIMAL AMOUNT OF PRODUCT LOST, NOTIFICATIONS WERE ONLY MADE TO THE SHIPPER FOR CORRECTIVE ACTION.

REGIONAL MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY DEAN L WHITELEY, SPARKS, NV., WAS NOTIFIED BY YARD MASTER DAN LEE SPARKS YARD, SPARKS, NV. AT 1320 HOURS OCTOBER 20, 1998,THAT SWITCH CREW REPORTED TANK CAR GATX 18592 SPOTTED IN TRACK #4 WAS LEAKING FROM BOTTOM OUTLET CAP. INSTRUCTED YARD MASTER NOT TO MOVE CAR AND ISOLATE IT FROM ANY SWITCHING ACTIVITY. INSPECTION FOUND LEAK COMING FROM 4 BOLT FLANGE SECURING THE TOP OPERATED BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE ASSEMBLY TO TANK CAR. NOTED OPERATING MECHANISM OF TOP OPERATED BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE PROTECTED WITH INTACT SEAL KELLER SEALS 1704973. HINGED COMBINATION HOUSING COVER WAS PROTECTED WITH INTACT SEAL KELLER SEALS 17044975. OPENED COMBINATION HOUSING RELIEVED INTERNAL PRESSURE FROM CAR THRU AIR VALVE. TIGHTENED TOP OPERATED BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE MECHANISM AND THIS SLOWED DRIPPING RELEASE. REMOVED BOTTOM OUTLET CAP DRAINING CAPTURED PRODUCT. OBSERVED ASSEMBLY FOR SEVERAL MINUTES AND NOTED NO FURTHER RELEASE. TIGHTENED CAP SCREWS ON 4 BOLT FLANGE. APPLIED SEAL UPF 329846 TO TOP OPERATED BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE AND SEAL UPF 329845 TO COMBINATION HOUSING COVER, HINGED MANWAY COVER LID WAS PROTECTED WITH INTACT SEAL KELLER SEALS 17044974 RMCC WAS FURNISHED DETAILS AND NOTIFIED CHEMTREC JEFF BOTWINICK WHO ASSIGNED INCIDENT #78312.

DEAN C COOPER, MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS CONTACTED BY MANAGER ERNEST SIROTEK, OAKLAND, CALIFORNIA, REPORTING A LEAKING TANK CAR AT YERMO, CALIFORNIA MANAGER SIROTEK HAD BEEN CONTACTED BY THE ST. LOUIS RMCC ACCOUNT THEY WERE UNABLE TO LOCATE MANAGER COOPER,  WHO WAS ADDRESSING AN OIL SPILL IN THE LYTLE CREEK AREA OF CAJON PASS. MANAGER SIROTEK HAD CONTACTED JIM ALDULAIMI, MANAGER, YARD OPERATIONS, YERMO, CALIFORNIA, WHO STATED THE CAR DEPARTMENT HAD OBSERVED LIQUID DRIPPING FROM THE BOTTOM PORTION OF THE ABOVE TANK CAR WHILE INSPECTING THE TRAIN ON YARD TRACK #206. MANAGER SIROTEK NOTIFIED CHEMTREC AND REQUESTED SHIPPER CONTACT. RMCC ALSO CONTINUED MAKING THEIR AGENCY NOTIFICATIONS. MANAGER COOPER CONTACTED MANAGER ALDULAIMI AND RECEIVED AND UPDATE. MANAGER ALDULAIMI HAD JUST RETURNED FROM LOOKING AT THE TANK CAR AND REPORTED THE DRIPPING HAD CEASED. MANAGER COOPER DROVE TO THE YERMO YARD AND LOCATED THE TANK CAR, 12 CAR LENGTHS FROM THE WEST END OF THE TRAIN. IT WAS NOTED THAT THIS WAS THE ORIGINAL TRAIN, LKY54-14, THAT ARRIVED YERMO AT 0100 HOURS, OCTOBER 15, 1998. INSPECTION DEVELOPED THIS CAR WAS EQUIPPED WITH A FULLY ENCLOSED SKID PLATE, WHICH COVERED THE SUMP. THERE WAS A 1/2 INCH OPENING AT THE ENDS OF THE SKID PROTECTION, WHERE PRODUCT COULD BE SEEING POOLED WITHIN THE CLOSURE. WHILE THE PRODUCT WAS NOT ACTIVELY LEAKING, THERE WAS Q SMALL AREA UNDER THE SKID PROTECTION AND BETWEEN THE RAILS (APPROXIMATELY 3 FEET) WHERE THE GROUND WAS CONTAMINATED. MANAGER COOPER CONTACTED CHARLES MONTOYA, PLANT MANAGER, PIONEER, AND ADVISED HIM  OF THE CONDITION OF THE TANK CAR.  MR. MONTOYA STATED HE HAD A TEAM RESPONDING FROM THE PLANT AND THEY SHOULD ARRIVE AT THE LOCATION WITHIN THE HOUR. IN ORDER TO FACILITATE THE TRAIN MOVEMENT, AN ENGINE WAS USED TO MOVE THE WEST END OF THE TRAIN, SEPARATING THE TANK FROM THE EAST END OF THE TRAIN. THE CAR WAS THEN SEPARATED FROM THE WEST END OF THE TRAIN AND LEFT IN PLACE. DURING THE MOVEMENT, SEVERAL GALLONS OF PRODUCT SLOSHED OUT OF THE SKID PLATE ONTO THE GROUND BETWEEN THE RAILS. REPRESENTATIVES FROM PIONEER ARRIVED AND USED SODA ASH TO SOLIDIFY THE PRODUCT WITHIN THE SKIP PLATE. SEVERAL BAGS WERE ALSO POURED INSIDE THE CAR TO SOLIDIFY THE RESIDUE IN THE SUMP. THE CONTAMINATED AREA  BETWEEN THE TRACKS WAS PICKED UP AND PLACED INTO SALVAGE DRUMS FOR CONTAINMENT. ONCE THE GROUND WAS FOUND TO BE WITHIN THE NEUTRAL PH RANGE, THE AREA WAS COVERED WITH SODA ASH. ARRANGEMENTS WERE MADE TO HAVE GATX PROVIDE A FIELD SERVICE VEHICLE, WHICH ARRIVED ON SATURDAY. THE SKID PROTECTION WAS CUT OFF IN ORDER TO GAIN ACCESS TO THE SUMP. INSPECTION NOTED A 1/4 INCH HOLE IN THE SIDE OF THE SUMP, WHICH WAS SECURED WITH A PATCH. ARRANGEMENTS WERE MADE TO ROUTE THE CAR TO THE GATX SERVICE FACILITY IN COLTON FOR INSPECTION AND REPAIRS.

column168: THE TANK CAR WAS FOUND TO BE LEAKING AFTER IT HAD BEEN SPOTTED INTO THE CAR REPAIR SHOP AT LIVONIA YARD. MOST OF THE SPILLAGE REMAINED ON THE TOP AND SIDES OF THE TANK CAR, ALTHOUGH A SMALL AMOUNT DID DRIP ONTO THE SHOP FLOOR. WOODALL MADE NOTIFICATION, VIA THE UPRR RISK MANAGEMENT COMMUNICATION CENTER, TO THE LOUISIANA STATE POLICE, THE LOUISIANA DEPT OF ENVIRONMENTAL QUALITY, THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER AND THE POINTE COUPEE PARISH 911 CENTER. ROBINSON AND MYERS NOTIFIED CHEMTREC AND WERE PLACED IN CONTACT WITH THE SHIPPER, GAYLOR CONTAINER. ARRANGEMENTS WERE MADE THROUGH GAYLORD FOR GATX INC TO RESPOND AND REPLACE A DEFECTIVE MANWAY GASKET. ADDITIONALLY CET ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES RESPONDED AND CLEANED UP THE SPILLAGE AND DECONTAMINATED THE TANK CAR AND THE CAR SHOP FLOOR AND REPLACE A DEFECTIVE MANWAY GASKET. ADDITIONALLY CET ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES RESPONDED AND CLEANED UP THE SPILLAGE AND DECONTAMINATED THE TANK CAR AND CAR SHOP FLOOR. MR. DAN LAMBER, AN ENVIRONMENTAL SPECIALIST WITH THE LOUISIANA  DEPT OF ENVIRONMENTAL QUALITY RESPONDED AND WAS SATISFIED THAT T THE INCIDENT WAS BEING HANDLED AND APPROPRIATELY BY UPRR.

column168: AB05398D, SHIPPER: PPG INDUSTRIES, AWB#DTP 4171213130NBL, 23:59, 10/07/98 AN ODOR WAS REPORTED TOPSIDE ON AIRCRAFT 935AX PARKED AT GATE D53 AT OUR SORT FACILITY LOCATED AT, ABX AIR INC., 145 HUNTER DRIVER, WILMINGTON, OHIO 45177. P/T SPILL TECHNICIANS CHUCK JONES AND TIM HINES RESPONDED TO THE ODOR, BEFORE ENTERING THE SCENE, THEY DONNED NOMEX SUITS, NOMEX HOODS, SELF CONTAINED BREATHING APPARATUS' FIRE HELMETS AND FIRE GLOVES.  THE ATMOSPHERE WAS MONITORED IN THE MAIN CARGO HOLD TOPSIDE DURING THE ENTIRE INVESTIGATION OF THE ODOR WITH A GX-86 GAS MONITOR.  THEY CHECK EACH "C" CONTAINER FOR THE ODOR, THEY FOUND THE ODOR TO BE EMITTING FROM A SHIPMENT CONTAINING PAINT.  THEY ISOLATED THIS SHIPMENT, PLACED IT INSIDE TWO PLASTIC BAGS AND REMOVED IT FROM THE AIRCRAFT.  THE AIRCRAFT WAS CHECKED FOR ANY REMAINING ODOR. THEY BROUGHT THE BAGGED SHIPMENT TO THE HAZ MAT DEPARTMENT FOR FURTHER INVESTIGATION, P/T SPILL TECHNICIANS DONNA RESOR AND BRUCE SHILTZ INVESTIGATED THE SHIPMENT. THEY FOUND THE SHIPMENT TO BE PROPERLY MARKED, LABELED AND CERTIFIED AS A REGULATED MATERIAL.  THEY OPENED THE BOX AND FOUND THE INNER METAL CONTAINER HAD AN UNSECURE CLOSURE CAUSING THE LEAKAGE OF 15 OUNCES OF PAINT WHICH CAUSE THE ODOR.  THEY RESEAL THE SHIPMENT, PLACED IT INSIDE TWO PLASTIC BAGS, AND PLACED IT IN A RECOVERY DRUM FOR TRANSPORT.  THIS SHIPMENT CONTAINS THE FOLLOWING HAZARDOUS MATERIAL:  PAINT, 3 UN1263, PKG GP III, CARGO AIRCRAFT ONLY.  THIS SHIPMENT WAS TRANSPORTED ONTO DESTINATION.

column42: HYDROGEN PEROXIDE, AQUEOUS SOLUTIONS WITH NOT LESS THAN 20 PERCENT BUT NOT MORE THAN 40 PERCENT HYDROGEN PEROXIDE (STABILIZED AS NECESSARY)
column168: Two one gallon jugs of hydrogen peroxide (35% mixture) packed in a three cu. ft. igloo cooler (as checked luggage) leaked onto the floor, causing damage to a portion of the aircraft floor and nearby luggage. As soon as the cause was determined and leaking material identified. Haz-mat officials were contacted and clean up initiated. Affected luggage on hand was separated and inspected by the haz mat team. Any employee that came in contact with this material were given an opportunity to seek medical attention. Those who did were treated and released. Passenger who checked the cooler was identified and questioned by the f.a.. and n.t.s.b., investigation is on going.

column168: 1755  ARRIVED AT PRICE AND UNLOADED FREIGHT. WHILE UNLOADING THE FREIGHT I NOTICED THAT TWO BAGS OF BANK MAIL WERE WET AT ONE END. UPON FURTHER INVESTIGATION I LOCATED THAT THE PACKAGE FROM ALLEN MEMORIAL HOSPITAL WAS LEAKING A FLUID AND HAD LEAKED ONTO THE TWO BANK BAGS. WE ISOLATED THE PACKAGE AND BANK BAGS OUTSIDE ON THE RAMP. 1810   I CALLED ALLEN MEMORIAL HOSPITAL AND TALKED WITH MS. HALEEN SWELLS IN THE LAB AND TOLD HER WHAT HAD HAPPENED AND ASKED HER TO TELL ME WHAT MIGHT BE LEAKING AND IF IT WAS HAZARDOUS. SHE SAID THAT IT WAS BIOPSY SPECIMENS PACKED IN A SOLUTION AND THAT WHAT LEAKING WAS PROBABLY FORMALDEHYDE. SHE ALSO INDICATED THAT  SHE THOUGHT IT WAS A BIOHAZARD. 1820   I CALLED THE CASTLE VIEW HOSPITAL LAB AND TALKED WITH MS. KELLY JENNINGS AND TOLD HER WHAT HAD HAPPENED AND THAT SHE NEEDED TO SEND SOMEONE FROM THE LAB TO THE AIRPORT TO POSITIVELY IDENTIFY THE LIQUID THAT HAD LEAKED AND IF IN DEED IT WAS HAZARDOUS. 1825   I REVIEWED HAZARDOUS MATERIAL PROTOCOL FROM THE REDTAIL AVIATION AND EXPRESS AIR OPERATIONS MANUALS. 1830   I CALLED EXPRESS AIR, INC., AND TALKED WITH MR. WAYNE REYNOLDS, CHIEF PILOT, AND EXPLAINED THE SITUATION AND WHAT HAD OCCURRED UP TO THE POINT. WAYNE AGREED THAT WE SHOULD CONFIRM THE LIQUID AND THEN GO FROM THERE. I AGREED TO CALL HIM AS SOON AS I KNEW SOMETHING. 1910   JEFF HUNT FROM THE PATHOLOGY LAB AT CASTLEVIEW HOSPITAL ARRIVED AND OPENED THE PACKAGE THAT HAD BEEN LEAKING. WE LOCATED SEVERAL LAB SPECIMENS SEALED IN PLASTIC CONTAINERS AND ENCLOSED IN HAZARDOUS MATERIAL BAGS. WE LOCATED A 600 CC CONTAINER THAT HAD BEEN LEAKING AROUND THE SEAL AND INTO THE HAZARDOUS MATERIAL BAG. THE HAZARDOUS MATERIAL BAG APPEARED TO ALSO BE LEAKING. THE CONTAINER WAS LABELED "BIPRODUCT OF CONCEPTION". JEFF TOLD ME THAT THE FLUID LEAKING WAS 10% FORMAL IN(UN #2209). HE SAID THAT IT WAS A HAZARDOUS MATERIAL AND AS LONG AS IT IS IN LIQUID FORM CARE SHOULD BE TAKEN. HE SAID THAT AFTER THE FLUID HAD DRIED ON THE BANK BAGS THEY WOULD BE OK TO TRANSPORT IN A CONFINED SPACE, LIKE AN AIRCRAFT, BUT NOT BEFORE. HE ALSO ASSURED US THAT THE BLOOD PRODUCTS WITH AFTER IT DRIES. JEFF TOOK THE LAB SAMPLES TO CASTLEVIEW HOSPITAL. I PLACED THE TWO BANK  BAGS IN A SHED FOR THE NIGHT TODRY OUT SO THEY COULD BR TRANSPORTED THE FOLLOWING MORNING. 1920   I TELEPHONED WAYNE AT EXPRESS AIR AND NOTIFIED HIM OF THE HAZARDOUS MATERIAL THAT WAS LOCATED AND WHAT HAD BEEN DONE WITH THEM, HE INSTRUCTED ME TO FILE THE APPROPRIATE REPORTS AND MAKE THE APPROPRIATE PHONE CALLS PER THE PROTOCOL IN THE OPERATIONS MANUAL. 1930   I TELEPHONED CHEMTREK AND FILED A REPORT WITH MR. MARK PETERSON. REPORT #78447.

File AB05498D, Shipper: Aldrich, ABE 7306870244 ARM. This is a 5800 form only. On 10/11/98, a spill was reported with an odor. The location of the spill was ABX Air Inc., 145 Hunter Drive, Wilmington, Oh 45177, in our haz mat sort facility. Haz mat coordinator, Ken Haag and part time spill technician, Donnor Resor responded. Upon arrival they discovered a brown fibreboard box emitting an odor. The outer box was properly marked and labeled and the proper haz mat certifications accompanied this shipment. Upon inspection of the inner contents, the following was found: one glass receptacle at 4 liters. The glass receptacle was placed in a plastic bag but was not sealed. The plastic bag was packed in styrofoam packing. Inspection of this shipment showed the closure to be loose under the packing tape. There were approximately two ounces of (methyl tert-butyl ether) class 3, flammable liquid, un2398, PG II, that leaked around the closure. This shipment was repacked into a recovery drum and returned to the shipper per their request.

THE OTHER BOXES IN THE SHIPMENT WERE ALSO INSPECTED FOR POSSIBLE UNDECLARED.  A CONTAINER OF GASOLINE WAS ALSO FOUND INSIDE ONE OF THE BOXES AND HAIR SPRAY AEROSOL ANOTHER.  THE BOXES CONTAINED VARIOUS ITEMS INCLUDING: 2 PAINT CANS OF LATEX PAINT, A CAMERA, A RADIO, AN ALARM CLOCK, A COOKING PAN, A RAZOR BLADE, TOOTH PASTE, A TOOL, A CALCULATOR, COMET, METAMUCIL, A STEEL MUG AND A SPOON, DEODORANT, BABY SHAMPOO, MULTIVITAMINS, PINSOL, LIMPIADOR LIQUIDO, ALGODOLY, MED. FEMININE NAPKINS, TINLEPAPE, TOILET PAPER, MARCA PROPIA MULTIUSOS, LIMIADOR, AGROSOL, PINTURE EN SPRAY, MELON 2 BOTTLES, TECH 2000 LIMPADOR, SUPER CONCENTRATED DEINYECTORES AND A NOTEBOOK. THE DESCRIPTIONS ON THE LABELING FOR MANY OF THE INNER CONTENTS WERE IN SPANISH.  FAA AGENT SYLVIA SAMANIEGO WAS NOTIFIED.  FEDEX WILL HOLD THE SHIPMENT PENDING FAA INVESTIGATION.

column168: PASSENGER MS. TONI HAPPNIE BOARDED FLIGHT 2472 (MCO-BOS)  WITH A PARTIALLY USED BOTTLE OF PUBLIX BRAND CHLORINE BLEACH.  THE BOTTLE WAS FOUND TO BE LEAKING DUE TO PASSENGER COMPLAINTS OF BURNING EYES AND RUNNY NOSES. FLIGHT ATTENDANT LUWANNA BROOKS ATTEMPTED TO CLEAN THE SMALL SPILL WHEN SHE REPORTED HAVE BURNING EYES, NASAL DISTRESS AND A SORE THROAT. FLIGHT 2472 WAS DIVERTED TO RDU AND EMS WAS REQUESTED TO MEET THE FLIGHT. AT APPROXIMATELY 1535 THE PASSENGERS OF FLIGHT 2472 WERE DEPLANED TO ALLOW MAINTENANCE TO CHECK AND CLEAN THE AIRCRAFT.  FLIGHT ATTENDANT LUWANNA BROOKS REFUSED TREATMENT BY EMS BUT WAS ALLOWED TO STAY IN RDU FOR THE EVENING TO RECOVER FROM HER REACTION TO THE BLEACH.  SHE REPORTED NO ILL EFFECT THE NEXT DAY. THE FLIGHT RETURNED TO NORMAL ROTATION AND THE PASSENGERS REPORTING THE SPILL WERE NOT INJURED.  FAA INSPECTION GARY DEAN WAS INFORMED OF THE INCIDENT AND RECEIVED INFORMATION AND PICTURES OF THE CHLORINE BLEACH.
