column168: AT APPROXIMATELY 08:30, A DRIVER ADVISED THE SUPERVISOR THAT THERE WAS A PACKAGE THAT WAS LEAKING ON THE FLOOR AT THE END OF THE CONVEYOR BELT. THE SUPERVISOR PROCEEDED TO PULL THE SHIPPER'S DECLARATION OFF THE PACKAGE OPENED THE DECK DOORS FOR VENTILATION AND WENT INTO THE OFFICE.  HE PROCEEDED TO CALL THE EMERGENCY PHONE NUMBER ON THE PAPERWORK, AND CONSEQUENTLY RECEIVED A FAX COPY OF THE MSDS FOR THIS SHIPMENT.  I WENT TO THE LOCATION OF THE SPILL WHERE I READ THE UN-NUMBER OFF FROM THE PACKAGE. I GRABBED A COPY OF AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE GUIDE BOOK ON MY WAY TO THE DISPATCH.  I CALLED BOTH THE FIRE DEPARTMENT AND OUR CORPORATE OFFICE TO REPORT THE SPILL WHILE I WAS LOOKING THE ITEM UP IN THE RESPONSE BOOK. THE BOOK STATED TO TRY TO PLACE SOME DIRT OR NONFLAMMABLE ABSORBANT MATERIAL ON THE SPILL IF POSSIBLE.  WE TRIED TO VENTILATE AS MUCH AS POSSIBLE. I DID SO AND TRIED KEEPING THE VEHICLES AND INDIVIDUALS AWAY FROM THE SPILL.  AT THIS TIME THE FIRE DEPARTMENT CALLED BACK AND ADVISED US TO EVACUATE THE BUILDING.

UPON ARRIVING AT KEYSTONE CEMENT THAT A SMALL QUANTITY OF MATERIAL HAD LEAKED FROM A PRESSURE RELIEF VALVE ON THE TOP OF THE TRAILER WHICH HAD IN ADVERTANITLY BEE LEFT OPEN BY THE DRIVER. BOTH THE SPILLAGE ON THE GROUND AND IN THE METAL HOSE TRAY WERE VERY QUICKLY AND EASILY CLEANED UP WITH NO COST INVOLVED. THE ABSORBENT MATERIAL WAS PROPERLY DISPOSED OF AT THE FACILITY.

THIS IS AN UNDECLARED HAZARDOUS MATERIAL SHIPMENT.  10-20-98, 00:29 A SPILL WAS REPORTED IN "B" BUILDING OF OUR SORT FACILITY LOCATED AT: ABX AIR INC., 145 HUNTER DRIVE, WILMINGTON, OH 45177.  PART TIME SPILL TECHNICIANS BRUCE SHILTZ AND CHUCK JONES RESPONDED TO THE SPILL.  UPON ARRIVAL THEY FOUND A BROWN FIBERBOARD BOX WITH VISIBLE SIGNS OF LEAKAGE.  THEY TESTED THE LIQUID WITH PH TEST PAPER, READING WAS NEUTRAL.  THEY OPENED THE BOX AND NOTICED AN ODOR EMITTING FROM THE OPEN BOX, THEY REGRESSED AND DONNED AIR PURIFYING RESPIRATORS WITH HEPA CARTRIDGES.  THEY INSPECTED THE CONTENTS OF THE BOX AND FOUND A BUBBLE AIR CUSHION BAG, A SHIPPING INVOICE AND 2 - 16 OUNCE PLASTIC SPRAY PUMP BOTTLES OF HOSPITAL OF HOSPITAL DISINFECTANT.  EACH BOTTLE INDICATES A FLAMMABLE WARNING AND THAT IT CONTAINS ISOPROPOL ALCOHOL.  THE CLOSURES WERE NOT SECURE BY POSITIVE MEANS CAUSING THE CLOSURES TO BECOME UNSECURE AND CAUSE A LEAKAGE OF APPROXIMATELY 7 OUNCES OF DISINFECTANT.  THEY SECURED THE CLOSURES ON THE BOTTLES, RESEALED THE BOX, PLACED IT INSIDE 2 PLASTIC BAGS AND PLACED IT INSIDE A RECOVERY DRUM.  THE RECOVERY DRUM WAS PLACED INSIDE THE HAZ MAT SECURITY CAGE UNDER LOCK AND KEY PENDING FAA  INVESTIGATION.  ALL AREAS INVOLVED WITH THIS SPILL WERE CLEANED BEFORE NORMAL OPERATIONS RESUMED.  CLEAR SCENE: 01:01. NOTE:  THE INVOICE WAS DAMAGED FROM THE LEAKAGE OF THE DISINFECTANT AND WAS NOT ABLE TO BE REPRODUCED.  THERE WERE NO MARKINGS, LABELS OR CERTIFICATION OF DANGEROUS GOOD ATTACHED TO THIS SHIPMENT TO INDICATE THE CONTENTS WERE A REGULATED MATERIAL.

MIKE BARTON WAS FILLING THE BULK TRUCK TO GO OUT ON A ROUTE.  HE HAD REMOVED THE WHEEL CHALKS FROM IN FRONT OF THE TIRES, AND WAS PREPARING TO DISCONNECT THE HOSES WHEN HE WENT TO ANSWER THE TELEPHONE.  WHEN HE RETURN TO THE TRUCK, HE GOT IN AND STARTED TO DRIVE OFF.  WHEN HE HEARD THE NOISE COMING FROM THE FILL HOSE SEPARATING, HE STOPPED THE TRUCK.  THIS PREVENTED THE VENT HOSE FROM SEPARATING BECAUSE IT WAS LONGER AND HE  HAD NOT YET USED UP THE SLACK IN THAT HOSE.  CARBON DIOXIDE WAS POURING OUT FROM THE LIQUID FILL HOSE SO THAT MIKE COULDN'T GO TO THE BACK OF THE TRUCK, OR INTO THE DEPOT TO SHUT OFF THE VALVE THAT FEEDS THE LIQUID FILL HOSE.

column168: DEAN C COOPER, MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS CONTACTED BY ST LOUIS  RMCC, REPORTING LEAKING CONTAINER AT THE ICTF.  MANAGER COOPER CONTACTED TIM POST, MANAGER, INTERMODAL, ICTF, WHO ADVISED THE CONTAINER WAS NOTED LEAKING AT THE REAR DOOR BY AN OUTSIDE DRAYMAN ATTEMPTING TO DELIVER THE CONTAINER.  THE CONTAINER WAS MOVED TO THE CUSTOMS DOCK WHERE IT COULD BE CONTAINED AND ISOLATED PENDING INSPECTION.  RMCC WAS REQUESTED TO NOTIFY CHEMTREC AND HAVE THEM FOLLOW UP WITH THERE SHIPPER CONTACT.  FOLLOW UP CONTACT WITH MANAGER POST DEVELOPED FOSS ENVIRONMENTAL WAS ON SITE AND PREPARING TO ADDRESS THE LEAK.  IT WAS NOT CLEAR WHO CONTACTED FOSS AS THE RAILROAD HAD YET TO HEAR FROM THE SHIPPER.  MANAGER POST WAS ADVISED TO HAVE THE FOSS PERSONNEL REMEDIATED THE PARKING AREA WHERE THE CONTAINER WAS ORIGINALLY LOCATED AS PART OF THE CLEAN UP PROCESS.  AS MANAGER COOPER WAS ENROUTE TO LOS ANGELES FROM ROSEVILLE, ALL COMMUNICATIONS WERE COMPLETED VIA CELLULAR PHONE. PRIOR TO ENTERING THE CONTAINER, IT WAS NOTED THAT THE LEAK APPEARED TO BE ISOLATED AT THE REAR OF THE CONTAINER.  AS SMALL AREA, ROUGHLY 8 INCHES WIDE, CENTERED ON THE CONTAINER AT THE DOOR OPENING, AND THE CHASSIS BELOW, WERE THE ONLY AREAS NOTED TO HAVE PRODUCT RESIDUE.  UPON OPENING THE DOORS, DEVELOPED THE DRUMS WERE DOUBLE STACKED AND SECURED WITH TY-GUARD MATERIAL.  THE DRUMS WERE DOUBLE BAYED WITH THE TY-GUARD MATERIAL ON EACH LEVEL, AND SECURED WITH TY-GARD RECOMMENDED DOUBLE STRIPS OF MATERIAL PER BAY.  THE CENTER BAY ON EACH LEVEL ENDED WITH A ROW OF 4 DRUMS, RATHER THAN A ROW OF 3.  THIS METHOD DOES NOT ALLOW FOR TIGHT COMPACTION OF THE DRUMS, AND IS NOT PER THE MANUFACTURERS PROPER APPLICATION OF THIS MATERIAL,  NOR IS IT AN APPROVED METHOD PER THE BOE 6-C.   UPON REMOVING THE TY-GUARD MATERIAL, THE UPPER AND LOWER REAR DOOR BAYS WERE REMOVED AND INSPECTED.  ON DRUM AT THE REAR OF THE LOAD HAD BEEN FLOOR LOADED, WHERE THE DRUM WAS OVER LAPPING THE STEEL DECK PLATE AND THE WOOD FLOORING.  THERE WAS A SLIGHT ELEVATION DIFFERENCE BETWEEN THE TWO, WHICH CAUSED THE BOTTOM CHIME OF THE DRUM TO ABRADE AGAINST THE DECK PLATE.  THE BOTTOM CHIME WORE THROUGH ENOUGH TO ALLOW THE PRODUCT TO WEEP FROM THE DRUM. INSPECTION OF THE DRUM INDICATED THAT 1-2 GALLONS OF PRODUCT LEAKED. THIS DRUM WAS THEN PLACED INTO AN OVERPACK AND SECURED.  THE FLOORING WAS DECONED AND THE REMAINING DRUMS WERE LOADED BACK INTO THE ORIGINAL CONTAINER.  AN EMPTY DRUM WAS UTILIZED TO FILL THE VOID OF THE DAMAGED DRUM.  THE LADING WAS THEN SECURED FOR MOVEMENT, AND THE CONTAINER WAS RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT ONTO THE CONSIGNEE.  THE OVER PACK WILL BE RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER PER THEIR INSTRUCTIONS. NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE TO CHEMTREC FOR REPORTING PURPOSES, AND TO THE SHIPPER FOR CORRECTIVE ACTION.
PETROMETER MALFUNCTIONED
